<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Visits Denver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji, disappointed by the  
failure of trade talks in Washington, said Saturday that pressure 
from China's opponents had merely delayed its entry into the World 
Trade Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu, speaking during a luncheon given by Denver Mayor Wellington  
Webb, said that after a meeting with a U.S. Congressional 
delegation ``one member whispered, `I am very sorry. Just wait 
another two months. I guarantee you that we will ratify that.''' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope we don't have to wait that long,'' Zhu said. He did not  
identify the member of Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu was greeted at the airport by about 150 Chinese-Americans  
waving U.S. and Chinese flags. 
</P>
<P>
	In downtown Denver, about 100 people protesting China's  
treatment of Tibet banged drums and shouted ``Free Tibet before 
free trade.'' Police arrested 23 people for failing to obey their 
orders, and TV reports showed handcuffed protesters being loaded 
onto buses. All were cited and released, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the protesters was former Chinese political prisoner Harry  
Wu, who told the crowd: ``The Chinese come over here with a smiling 
face, but they have bloody hands.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu also met with Gov. Bill Owens.  
</P>
<P>
	The premier last week met with President Clinton and spent four  
days in negotiations, hoping to win China entry into the World 
Trade Organization. He offered to lower tariff barriers for 
American financial service firms, telecommunication companies and 
other U.S. industries hoping to gain entry to China's market. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, faced with congressional anger over  
allegations of Chinese nuclear espionage and human rights 
violations, demanded more concessions. In the end, Clinton vetoed a 
final deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
