<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 21:12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Tours Broncos' HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- When asked what he wanted to do during his visit  
to Colorado, China premier Zhu Rongji had only one request: He 
wanted to visit the home of the two-time Super Bowl champion Denver 
Broncos. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu showed no disappointment when neither quarterback John Elway  
nor any other members of the Broncos failed to show up for his 
visit to their training camp Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't really start next season's program until July, so not  
many players are around these days,'' Broncos owner Pat Bowlen 
said, explaining the absence of his players. 
</P>
<P>
	Elway did attend a dinner for Zhu on Saturday evening.  
</P>
<P>
	At the training facility, members of the Chinese delegation  
laughed as they took turns trying to throw the football with some 
former Broncos, and the premier joked as he got a few pointers of 
his own. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just use one hand,'' he was told after lobbing the football  
with both hands to former Bronco Steve Sewell. 
</P>
<P>
	After Zhu threw the football toward Sewell but hit a nearby  
television camera instead, Sewell gently tossed it back to the 
premier. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's not throwing it as hard as he can because he's being  
polite to me,'' Zhu said with a laugh. ``It's because I am a 
guest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During his visit to the Denver area, which included a luncheon  
hosted by Mayor Wellington Webb, a trip to Red Rocks Amphitheater, 
a tour of the Storage Technology facilities and dinner with Gov. 
Bill Owens, Zhu received numerous gifts. Among them were two 
footballs signed by the Super Bowl champs and several glass 
souvenirs. 
</P>
<P>
	The premier said he was particularly pleased with the Broncos  
jersey Bowlen gave him, with Elway's No. 7 and his own name -- 
``ZHU'' -- printed on the back. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu and his delegation were given a tour of the Broncos training  
center and the premier called the facilities ``purely first 
class.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zhu was also told about the types of injuries that befall  
football players and shown the pads and other protective gear worn 
on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like what ancient combat warriors would wear,'' Zhu said  
as he declined an offer to try on some pads. ``I don't think I 
could handle it. I would just fall down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The premier also invited the Super Bowl champions to visit China  
when they travel to Australia for an exhibition game next year. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
