<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Chill Triggers Whine Season </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Southern Californians, their closets full of  
tank tops and shorts, are whining about the big chill. 
</P>
<P>
	A relatively frigid spring had residents bundled up in  
sweatshirts, jackets and gloves, and talking about temperatures 
Friday even colder than some spots in Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	The thin-skinned populace in a region synonymous with sun joined  
in the question: Where's spring? 
</P>
<P>
	``I know we have weird weather here but this is too much. I like  
it hot,'' said Sharon Armstrong as she munched a taco downtown. 
``Now, I say forget about the beach. I just want to get home and 
get under my blanket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cold yes, but unbearable?  
</P>
<P>
	``Shut up and deal with it,'' said Billy Neal, 45, of suburban  
Tujunga. ``In Detroit when its 30 or 40 degrees they think it's a 
nice day. Trouble is, that's why we live in Southern California. 
It's so nice all the time. 
</P>
<P>
	A mantle of fresh snow coated the San Gabriel and San Bernardino  
mountains, where high-country dwellers were forced to install tire 
chains for trips to higher elevations. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest spring rainstorm, with another due this weekend,  
swept east into Arizona during the night leaving clear skies and 
sunrise lows in the upper 30s and 40s in most areas. Downtown Los 
Angeles reported 45 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	Oxnard, 60 miles west of Los Angeles, set a new record low of 36  
degrees. The previous low for the date was 37 in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not THAT cold,'' said Susie Shellabarger, a receptionist  
at the Endless Summer tanning salon in Ventura County. ``But I'm 
pregnant, so I'm always hot anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just before dawn, it was 18 degrees -- a record -- atop snowcapped  
Mt. Wilson, 21 miles northeast of Los Angeles, where the wind-chill 
was 11 below zero. At the same hour in Fairbanks, Alaska, it was a 
balmy 19 with a 2-degree wind-chill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
