<DOCNO> APW19990410.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 07:14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Quarterbacks Big Draw of NFL Draft </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- So much for the ``best available athletes,'' the  
players every coach says he'll draft regardless of position. 
</P>
<P>
	When the NFL draft begins Saturday, those players -- Ricky  
Williams, Champ Bailey, Chris Claiborne, Torry Holt and Jevon 
Kearse -- will wait while Tim Couch, Akili Smith, Donovan McNabb and 
Daunte Culpepper are chosen. 
</P>
<P>
	That's because Couch and his co-stars are quarterbacks, and this  
is the best draft for QBs since 1983, when six went in the first 
round. Two of those six, John Elway and Dan Marino, are sure Hall 
of Famers, and a third, Jim Kelly, has a good shot. 
</P>
<P>
	On the other hand ...  
</P>
<P>
	``You're not going to look five years from now and say, `Boy,  
all these guys are great.' Down the road it might be just two of 
them,'' said Indianapolis Colts coach Jim Mora, who made a good 
choice last season by drafting Peyton Manning over Ryan Leaf at No. 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	History says Mora's right.  
</P>
<P>
	Of the three other first-round QBs in '83, Ken O'Brien and Tony  
Eason, had ordinary careers, and Todd Blackledge, the second 
quarterback taken (after Elway), was a bust. 
</P>
<P>
	So while Williams, who set an NCAA rushing record at Texas and  
won the Heisman Trophy, is an obvious No. 1, he'll probably have to 
wait a few minutes at the draft, just as friend and new Hall of 
Famer Eric Dickerson did when he was taken No. 2 behind Elway in 
'83. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's draft could also be socially historic.  
</P>
<P>
	The probable first-round quarterbacks are Couch of Kentucky,  
Smith of Oregon, McNabb of Syracuse, Culpepper of Central Florida 
and Cade McNown of UCLA. Smith, Culpepper and McNabb are black, as 
is another possible first rounder, Shaun King of Tulane. 
</P>
<P>
	For whatever reason, only three black quarterbacks have been  
taken in the first round -- Doug Williams in 1978, Andre Ware in 
1990 and Steve McNair in 1995. Warren Moon, third behind Marino and 
Elway in career yards passing, went undrafted in 1978 and had to go 
to Canada to prove himself. 
</P>
<P>
	While times have changed, so have styles. Of the top group, only  
Couch is the prototypical dropback passer NFL scouts have liked for 
so long. 
</P>
<P>
	If Couch, Smith and McNabb go 1-2-3 to Cleveland, Philadelphia  
and Cincinnati, the teams behind them benefit. Indianapolis, for 
example, picks fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colts, who have Manning, need defense, like Bailey, the  
Georgia cornerback; Kearse, the Florida linebacker, and Claiborne, 
the Southern Cal linebacker. 
</P>
<P>
	They also could take Williams and trade Marshall Faulk for more  
picks. 
</P>
<P>
	The expansion Browns get the first pick and have narrowed it  
down to Couch, Smith or Williams. Figure Couch or Smith -- coach 
Chris Palmer is a quarterback guru and it's easier to build around 
a QB. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia probably will use the second pick on a QB. The  
Eagles love McNabb and Williams, but most likely will take Smith or 
Couch, whoever doesn't go to Cleveland. Cincinnati would then take 
McNabb, although Bailey is an option. 
</P>
<P>
	Culpepper could go to Chicago at No. 7 or Baltimore at No. 10,  
and McNown, rated fifth among quarterbacks by most teams, could go 
as high as 12th to New Orleans, which has offered its entire draft 
and part of next year's for Williams. If McNown gets by the Saints, 
he probably won't get by Tampa Bay, No. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	King could go at the end of the first and so could Ohio State  
quarterback Joe Germaine. Either might go to San Francisco, which 
made a major mistake two years ago by taking Jim Druckenmiller 
instead of Jake Plummer as Steve Young's eventual successor. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is quality and there is depth, which is unusual,'' said  
Tom Modrak, director of player personnel for the Eagles. ``Most 
years, you see a choice between two quarterbacks. There's a choice 
between more now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As usual, a lot of offensive linemen will go high -- many  
drafters believe in the ``Save the Whales'' philosophy expounded by 
George Young, the former New York Giants general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest whale is 6-foot-7 Aaron Gibson of Wisconsin, who  
entered college at 427 pounds and is leaving at about 375. The best 
may be John Tait of Brigham Young. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond Williams and Edgerrin James of Miami, there aren't many  
first-round running backs, although Rob Konrad of Syracuse is a 
fullback who can run like Tampa Bay's Mike Alstott and blocks 
better. 
</P>
<P>
	The best wide receiver is North Carolina State's Holt, a  
top-five pick in most years. He's followed by David Boston of Ohio 
State, with Louisiana Tech's Troy Edwards coming up quickly. 
(Boston's father, Byron, is an NFL official who won't be allowed to 
work his son's games). 
</P>
<P>
	The most intriguing prospect may be troubled running back Cecil  
Collins, who on Thursday pleaded guilty to charges that he fondled 
two women. He will be on supervised parole for four years but will 
still be able to play in the NFL. 
</P>
<P>
	He was in a total of only six college games at LSU and McNeese  
State, in part because of his run-ins with the law. He never ran 
for fewer than 172 yards in three starts for the Tigers. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami is interested -- Jimmy Johnson has a history of working  
with troubled players. And although Collins probably won't go in 
the first round, he could go in the second. 
</P>
<P>
	But this year nobody moves up like the quarterbacks.  
</P>
<P>
	Should they?  
</P>
<P>
	I'm always amused,'' Johnson said. ``On the surface you'd say,  
`Well, this is a strong draft for quarterbacks.' Well, if these 
first five or six quarterbacks turn into duds, then it's a horrible 
draft for quarterbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's only a good draft if you pick good players and they play  
good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990410.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 13:41:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chevrolet Pulls Plug on '99 Monte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) -- Chevrolet's struggles to get its new Monte  
Carlo on the track during the 1999 Winston Cup season ended 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. announced that it was halting its bid to  
win NASCAR's approval of the new car in time to get it on the track 
this year, and that the 2000 Monte Carlo's Winston Cup debut would 
wait until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Since most Chevrolet teams had been operating for several weeks  
on the assumption that the new car would not be ready this year, 
Saturday's announcement was a mere formality. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevrolet marketing general manager Kurt Ritter said that even  
if NASCAR were to approve the car immediately, Monte Carlo teams 
don't think they could get a car ready this year without 
jeopardizing their 1999 title chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot ask them to take such a risk,'' Ritter said.  
</P>
<P>
	Chevrolet's 12-month quest to get the Monte Carlo approved by  
the sport's sanctioning body has resulted in a car that, according 
to Ritter, would be ``uncompetitive on the race track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR officials elected against responding to Ritter's  
assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said the decision to delay the introduction of the race car  
would not affect the street version of the 2000 Monte Carlo, which 
remains on schedule for retail delivery late this summer. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WALTRIP'S LAMENT:* Darrell Waltrip leads all drivers with 12  
victories at Bristol Motor Speedway, but he isn't terribly fond of 
racing on the .533-mile, high-banked oval. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason? When Waltrip was younger, the starting fields at  
Bristol generally were limited to 34 or 36 cars. Now the fields are 
43, a number that Waltrip feels cramps an already tight track. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leader takes the green flag and the 43rd guy is in the  
middle of the back straightaway,'' he said. ``In 20 laps the leader 
is lapping the back of the field. That's not good racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TIME TRIALS:* John Andretti led Saturday's second-round  
qualifying for the Food City 500 with a fast lap of 123.905 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Andretti gone that fast in Friday's opening round of time  
trials when the top 25 starting spots were set, he would have 
earned the 12th position. Instead, he will start 26th on Sunday's 
43-car grid. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven drivers failed to earn one of the top 36 spots available  
to the fastest qualifiers and had to take provisional starting 
spots. They were Johnny Benson, Ward Burton, Ernie Irvan, Chad 
Little, Jeremy Mayfield, Steve Park and Michael Waltrip. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing to make the field were Stanton Barrett, Rich Bickle,  
Derrike Cope and Carl Long. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EARNHARDT WRECK:* Seven-time Winston Cup champion Dale  
Earnhardt crashed his Chevrolet in Saturday's final practice 
session. Earnhardt was not injured, but he will have to switch to a 
backup car for Sunday's race, forcing him to start from the rear of 
the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Television replays showed Earnhardt appeared to lose control of  
his car as he went down the frontstretch, setting off a long slide 
that ended when the front end of his car slammed into the concrete 
retaining wall near the first turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was loose up off the corner,'' Earnhardt said. ``We kept  
working on it, but it just got out from under me. We'll unload the 
backup car and see if we can get it ready. We can come back and win 
from where we're at.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *C'EST LA VIE:* Michael Waltrip tried to be philosophical about  
damaging the right rear end of his car in a crash during 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all going to look like this sooner or later at Bristol  
anyway,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
