<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> USOC Unveils Plan To Bounce Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The U.S. Olympic Committee unveiled a $9  
million plan Saturday to bounce back from the scandal of Salt Lake 
and restore public trust in the games. 
</P>
<P>
	A combination of image-building and concrete safeguards against  
corruption, the plan was announced by executive director Dick 
Schultz at the USOC's first meeting since the $1 million bribery 
scandal in Utah broke late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	From his opening reference to an Oscar night joke by Whoopi  
Goldberg concerning the perception that Olympic officials had their 
price, Schultz made it clear the games' community faced 
unprecedented problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``You know you've reached a new low when they're telling jokes  
about you on the world's stage,'' he said. ``It is hard to 
exaggerate the seriousness of the challenge we face and have been 
facing since the scandal began to unfold in Salt Lake City last 
November.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schultz noted that USOC polls had found a drop in public  
confidence in the Olympics, from 36 percent in January to 32 
percent last month, although support for the athletes and sponsors 
of the games remained high. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the new program, to be launched on a national Olympic  
Day June 23, would be aimed at restoring ``a trust between the 
people of the world and the Olympic movement, a trust that is now 
held up to ridicule by our most popular entertainers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The USOC, Schultz said, would focus on past triumphs and future  
gold medalists to present the best image of the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``At the heart of the Olympic dream, you discover the American  
dream -- the chance for any individual to rise above their 
circumstances and fulfill their destiny,'' the executive director 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, he said, the committee would ask the  
consulting company of McKinsey &AMP; Co. to help analyze its rules and 
structure and make ``changes necessary to ensure that the USOC is a 
model of ethical and management efficiency in the next 
millennium.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Through the first half of the two-day meeting, the Salt Lake  
scandal -- a scheme to buy votes of International Olympic Committee 
members in the Utah capital's successful bid for the 2002 Winter 
Games -- was the dominant theme. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtually every speaker made some reference to the case that had  
led to the expulsion of six IOC members, changes in the rules for 
Olympic site selection and creation of two elite panels to 
restructure the international committee and oversee its members 
behavior. 
</P>
<P>
	``This has been a difficult time, an extraordinary time, and I  
hope a time that won't be repeated,'' IOC vice president Anita 
DeFrantz told the board meeting. ``It's part of our history and it 
won't go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Garff, the chairman of the Salt Lake Organizing  
Committee, said the operators of the games were having trouble 
raising the final $300 million in their $1.7 billion budget, and 
were making contingency plans in case they came up short. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it was all the fault of a couple of overzealous bidders  
almost a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I apologize for the actions of a few that have embarrassed so  
many,'' Garff said. ``I am chagrined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even the USOC's budget, vibrant with $104.3 million income last  
year and an unexpected $6.8 million cash surplus, took a hit. It 
included $1 million in unexpected legal fees resulting from the 
Salt Lake scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	They also included legal counsel to help collect information for  
an independent ethics investigation headed by former Senate 
Majority Leader George Mitchell and a Justice Department 
investigation into possible federal law violations in the Salt Lake 
case. The USOC turned over more than 200,000 documents to those two 
inquiries. 
</P>
<P>
	Mitchell, whose report placed most of the blame for the Salt  
Lake scandal on the IOC, is scheduled to brief the USOC on his 
investigation Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Maine Democrat, who helped broker the Northern Ireland peace  
plan, also is scheduled to testify Wednesday before the Senate 
Commerce Committee on the Olympic scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	He will be joined by members of his commission; USOC president  
Bill Hybl; and the IOC's two U.S. members, DeFrantz and Jim Easton. 
IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch declined an invitation to 
testify. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, Sen. John McCain, the Commerce Committee chairman,  
has called for testimony from one of the Olympic community's 
harshest critics -- Andrew Jennings, whose 1992 book, ``The Lords of 
the Rings,'' painted a picture of corruption and influence 
peddling. 
</P>
<P>
	The book also detailed Samaranch's role as an official in the  
regime of former Spanish dictator Francisco Franco. 
</P>
<P>
	Hybl and DeFrantz have been appointed to a commission, IOC 2000,  
to recommend sweeping changes in the international committee's 
membership and structure. Also on that panel are former Secretary 
of State Henry Kissinger and Los Angeles Olympic organizer Peter 
Ueberroth. 
</P>
<P>
	Samaranch, hoping to prove that the IOC is serious about  
changing the clubby practices it has followed for the last 105 
years, also announced Friday an eight-member ethics commission, 
including former United Nations Secretary General Javier Perez de 
Cuellar and former Senate Majority Leader and White House Chief of 
Staff Howard Baker. 
</P>
<P>
	DeFrantz said such actions, taken at ``warp speed,'' proved the  
IOC took reform to heart. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe we will do the things we must do to preserve the  
Olympic ideal,'' she said. ``I believe we will do the things it 
takes to make sure the games flourish.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
