<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Student Reunion Floods Fla. Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- The road to this resort city turned  
to gridlock as thousands of black students converged for a weekend 
of partying amid controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials had predicted the traffic jam during ``Black College  
Reunion'' and had hoped to restrict access by requiring passes to 
drive to the beach. But U.S. District Judge Patricia Fawcett ruled 
Thursday that the plan unfairly singled out the Black College 
Reunion. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's reunion weekend erupted in violence when a man was  
killed and four police officers wounded during a shootout. Police 
complained that traffic was so congested that reinforcements and 
medical help had great difficulty reaching the shooting scene. 
</P>
<P>
	Black College Reunion started in 1984 as a small gathering of  
students from Florida A&AMP;M University in Tallahassee and from nearby 
Bethune-Cookman College. It now competes with Atlanta's Freaknik as 
the place to go for a ``black spring break.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cruising, partying and ogling members of the opposite sex are  
the primary activities of the event, which is expected to bring in 
more than 100,000 students today. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officers, stationed Friday on about every corner and  
throughout the beach corridor, said they had made 143 arrests as of 
5 a.m. today, mainly for misdemeanors but four for gun violations. 
About 400 citations have been written so far. Last year, 329 
arrests were made and 926 citations written over the three-day 
event. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said that so far it has been no different than the recent  
Bike Week, a motorcycle festival. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was absolutely nothing serious. We're not complaining,''  
said police spokeswoman Cherri Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everybody was thrilled with the police presence, though.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't stand all these police,'' said Brian Green, 25, a  
Miami-area resident and graduate of the University of Alabama. 
``We're just out here to have a good time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the few white people at the beach was Angel Byrd, an  
18-year-old from Orlando. Some celebrants gathered around her as 
she walked with a friend and nearly succeeded in removing her 
bikini top. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all just fun and games,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The city lost out in its effort to restrict traffic after the  
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People and 
three residents sued the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
