<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 00:31:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maggert, Faldo Fail To Make Cut  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Jeff Maggert picked up a $1 million paycheck  
for winning the Match Play championship. It won't be enough to buy 
a green jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, Maggert staggered away from the 18th hole at Augusta  
National Golf Club, made do with a payday of $5,000 and headed home 
for the weekend after missing the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The 35-year-old Texan, who won the Match Play championship in  
February, was joined on the sidelines by three-time Masters 
champion Nick Faldo and two-time winners Ben Crenshaw, Seve 
Ballesteros and Tom Watson. 
</P>
<P>
	Maggert shot a 6-under-par 78 in the first round, then added a  
76 on Friday to finish with a 10-over 154, missing the cut by six 
strokes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of the four majors, this is the toughest one for me,'' said  
Maggert, who hasn't finished higher than 37th since his surprise 
victory in the Match Play Championship. ``It's a tough course. 
Maybe I haven't played it enough yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has cracked the top 20 only once in seven trips to the  
Masters -- tying for seventh in 1996 -- and missed the cut three 
times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like someday I'm going to have a good tournament  
here,'' Maggert said. ``I just have to stay patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Already assured of a banner year, Maggert would prefer that it  
be remembered for more than just his Match Play victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's over and done with,'' he said. ``I've got to get out of  
here and play some good golf. That's what I'll try to do in the 
next few weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Faldo hasn't played very well since the 1996 Masters, when he  
rallied from a six-stroke deficit in the final round for a 
memorable victory over Greg Norman. 
</P>
<P>
	The 41-year-old Englishman has now missed the cut three years in  
a row at Augusta National, raising doubts he will ever regain the 
swing that made him one of the world's most dominant players. He 
was doomed by an 80 in the first round, finishing 9-over after a 73 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a fine line at the moment,'' said Faldo, whose 80 was his  
second-worst round in 16 trips to the Masters. ``I've had a million 
blows this year, and this is just another one to overcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The affable Crenshaw, whose victory in the 1995 Masters was  
among the tournament's most emotional moments, couldn't bear to 
talk with reporters after another disastrous trip to Augusta. He 
has missed the cut three of the last four years, shooting a 79 on 
Friday to finish at 153. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's too painful,'' Crenshaw said, before hurrying away to  
brood in the clubhouse. 
</P>
<P>
	Ballesteros, playing on his 42nd birthday, didn't seem all that  
bothered after missing the cut for the third year in a row. At 
least he was consistent, knocked out by consecutive rounds of 78. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just enjoying myself and trying to play well,'' said  
Ballesteros, the Masters champion in 1980 and '83. ``It's always 
nice to be here. That's a positive thing, especially since I have 
won before.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Watson appeared in good shape, sitting at 2-over with just four  
holes to play. But his game began to fall apart at 15, when he 
chipped from behind the green into the water along the front, 
leading to a bogey. At the par-3 16th, his tee shot landed in the 
front bunker, and he was still there after his next shot. Finally 
on the green in three, Watson two-putted for a double-bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Watson put his tee shot into the pine trees at 18, then  
three-putted for another double-bogey to finish with at 151. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a tough finish,'' Watson said. ``I played pretty well  
other than the last four holes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Four amateurs -- Sergio Garcia (147), Tom McKnight (147), Matt  
Kuchar (148) and Trevor Immelman (148) -- made the cut, the most to 
reach the weekend since 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar, the sensation of the 1998 tournament, came to Augusta  
battling the flu and shot a 77 in the first round. But he felt 
better Friday and came through with a 71, highlighted by a 4-under, 
three-hole stretch on the back nine. 
</P>
<P>
	Kuchar sandwiched two birdies around an eagle at the par-5 13th,  
when he holed out from a bunker. The Georgia Tech junior bogeyed 
the final two holes but still managed to make the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty-three-year-old Gary Player, a three-time Masters champion,  
couldn't duplicate his performance a year ago, when he became the 
oldest player to make the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	The South African had two straight rounds of 79 to finish  
14-over, but he managed to thrill the fans at 18 when his 60-foot 
putt snaked down the hilly green to within a foot of the hole, 
allowing him to tap out for par. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's always a thrill to come here,'' Player said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
