<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bobbyjo Wins Grand National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIVERPOOL, England (AP) -- It was 24 years between victories for  
an Irish-bred horse in the Grand National and again the winner was 
ridden by a Carberry. 
</P>
<P>
	Bobbyjo, with 25-year-old Irishman Paul Carberry in the saddle,  
won the Grand National on Saturday by 10 lengths over Blue Charm. 
In 1975, Tommy Carberry, Paul's father and Bobbyjo's trainer, won 
the famed steeplechase race aboard L'Escargot. 
</P>
<P>
	Carberry, hugged by his father at the finish line after an  
acrobatic dismount, described the Irish sweep as ``a dream come 
true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a good start and were handy throughout,'' he said. ``He  
jumped very well and as we jumped the last I knew he would quicken. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can't get any better than that. It'll take a while to set  
in but it was worth going to bed at nine last night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Carberry said he suffered more during the race than  
his son. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think when you're riding in the race it goes quickly, but  
when you're standing as a trainer it takes a very long time,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	London-based Irish owner Bobby Burke, who named the horse for  
himself and his wife, Jo, was also thrilled. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't describe it, it's just fantastic,'' Burke said. ``I'm  
delighted for Tommy Carberry, I'm happier for Tommy more than 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Call it a Day, ridden by two-time winner Richard Dunwoody, was  
third and Addington Boy finished fourth in the 4 1/4-mile race that 
covers 30 jumps. 
</P>
<P>
	The only mare in the race, Fiddling the Facts, went off as the  
6-1 favorite as an estimated $112 million was wagered in one of the 
most important days of year in British sports. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue Charm led for much of the race and was ahead over the final  
jump with five or six horses still in contention until Bobbyjo 
pulled away down the stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen of the 32 horses finished the difficult course and one,  
Eudipe, was killed as he went down over the 22nd jump with four 
other horses also falling at the same hurdle. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year only six horses finished and three were killed,  
setting off protests by animal-rights activists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
