<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talent Agents Protested Over Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Civil rights activists marched on  
two major Hollywood talent agencies in support of a group of black 
concert promoters who claim they are excluded from working with 
white performers and top black acts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sixty demonstrators gathered outside William Morris Agency on  
Friday and then walked to the offices of Creative Artists Agency. 
Both companies are among defendants named in a $700 million lawsuit 
five promoters filed in New York City last November. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are hurting the opportunity for the black community,''  
said the Rev. Joseph Lowery, a former president of the Southern 
Christian Leadership Conference. ``As we were lynched physically 
years ago, we're being lynched economically today by the William 
Morris and Creative Artists and others. They are the new lynch 
mob.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Morris and CAA said the accusations are false.  
</P>
<P>
	``Allegations that the William Morris Agency engages in  
exclusionary practices, condones racism or discriminates in any way 
against minorities -- in and out of the music business -- are not 
only unthinkable but false and inflammatory,'' said company 
spokesman Don DeMesquita. 
</P>
<P>
	The promoters are suing 11 talent agencies and 29 promoters,  
claiming they are excluded from promoting major acts once they 
reach star status. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit also claims white promoters pressure booking agents  
to join in a conspiracy against black promoters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
