<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour Against Police Violence Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson on Saturday kicked off an  
eight-day national tour to raise awareness of police violence 
against minorities and said the killing of an unarmed man in New 
York shows it is ``open season on blacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson was joined at a rally at his Rainbow/PUSH Coalition  
headquarters by the parents of Amadou Diallo, the West African 
immigrant shot 19 times in February by four white New York police 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers, who said they thought Diallo was about to turn a  
weapon on them, have since been indicted on second-degree murder 
charges. 
</P>
<P>
	``At least when you are violated by a stranger or a neighbor ...  
you can call the police,'' Jackson said. ``But when the policeman 
is the bearer of violence and empowered by the state with a badge 
and a gun, that's terrorism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is open season on blacks,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Diallo's mother, Kadiadou Diallo, told the hundreds of people  
that blacks and others should unite to end injustice, no matter 
what their differences. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson and the Rev. Al Sharpton, who has led protests in New  
York in the wake of the Diallo shooting, said police misdeeds 
against minorities are rampant across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson said most of those arrested in the United States are  
white, but most of those who go to prison are black. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cards are stacked,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
