<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eatery Wants Names From Yahoo! </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- A Nashville-based restaurant chain has  
asked a judge to force Internet hub Yahoo! to reveal who placed 
confidential company data on the Internet using the names of its 
top executives. 
</P>
<P>
	The postings about Shoney's, Inc. on a Yahoo! message board  
purported to reveal closure plans for poorly performing restaurants 
and a possible company bankruptcy filing, according to the lawsuit 
filed Friday in Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the bogus e-mail aliases used to post the data were the  
names of Shoney's president, J. Michael Bodnar, and its chairman, 
Raymond Schoenbaum, who have worked to revive the company after 
years of declining sales and stock prices. At least one of the 
postings was made on March 7. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for the restaurant are requesting a judge subpoena  
Yahoo! for the names of those who created the e-mail accounts so 
their names can be added to a related lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the information in the postings was true, but the  
company has no plans to file for bankruptcy, Shoney's spokeswoman 
Betty J. Marshall said. The company suspects the postings were 
placed by a current or former employee. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is not our intention to prohibit criticism or personal  
opinion about the company,'' Marshall said. ``But we have an 
obligation to protect confidential and proprietary information 
about Shoney's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! officials did not return a call for comment on Saturday.  
</P>
<P>
	Shoney's operates and franchises about 1,200 Shoney's, Captain  
D's, Pargo's and Fifth Quarter restaurants in 28 states. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, the company announced a first-quarter loss of $15.9  
million. It closed 104 restaurants in 1998 and projected more would 
close this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, a falsified Internet posting about PairGain  
Technologies sent the company's stock surging before the story 
could be debunked. 
</P>
<P>
	Also this year, Raytheon Co. got subpoenas demanding Yahoo!  
provide information on employees discussing business issues on an 
Internet forum. Yahoo! complied and two workers reportedly resigned 
from the defense contractor. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
