<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Bombs Falling on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite bad weather limiting NATO  
air operations, bombs fell on Kosovo and air-raid sirens blared in 
several other Yugoslav cities today, the eve of Christian Orthodox 
Easter. Dismissing a holiday weekend cease-fire as a sham, NATO 
signaled there was little likelihood of a letup in airstrikes 
tomorrow, the day Serbians celebrate Easter. The alliance also 
reported today that the campaign had so far destroyed half of 
Yugoslavia's most modern fighter planes. 

</P>
<P>
	More U.S. Firepower to Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO is expecting to add dozens of aircraft to  
its arsenal used in the bombing of Yugoslavia within days, 
officials said. The Pentagon announced today that 82 more U.S. 
planes would join the airstrikes, a move to intensify the battle 
against Serb forces. But it could take a month for 24 Apache attack 
helicopters to be ready for use from a base in Albania. Their 
introduction would mark an escalation of the war and for the first 
time allow close-to-the-ground, direct strikes against Serb troops 
and tanks during persistent bad weather. 

</P>
<P>
	Mother of Captured GI Breaks Down  
</P>
<P>
	MONTEBELLO, Calif. (AP) -- The mother of one of the American  
soldiers captured on the Yugoslav border broke down at a ceremony 
attended by hundreds today. ``He went on a mission of peace. This 
was not supposed to happen,'' Vivian Ramirez said of her son, Army 
Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez. Ramirez, 24, Staff Sgt. Christopher 
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 22, 
of Huntsville, Texas, were captured March 31 while patrolling the 
Yugoslav-Macedonia border. Shouts of encouragement for Mrs. Ramirez 
came from the audience of about 300 people gathered before the 
veterans memorial at Montebello Park. 

</P>
<P>
	Tornado Victims Begin Cleanup  
</P>
<P>
	BLUE ASH, Ohio (AP) -- A day after a tornado sliced through  
Cincinnati's northern suburbs, killing four and destroying hundreds 
of homes, residents today hurried to salvage their belongings 
before another round of forecasted storms raked the area. The state 
Emergency Management Agency estimated today that 900 homes were 
damaged in Hamilton, Clinton and Warren counties in southwest Ohio. 
Red Cross shelters remained open while police sealed off streets so 
repair crews could restore electricity and clear debris. 

</P>
<P>
	Home of Suspected Spy Searched  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The New Mexico home of a scientist fired from  
his job at the Los Alamos National Laboratory under suspicion he 
passed nuclear weapons secrets to China was searched by FBI agents 
today. Energy Secretary Bill Richardson confirmed the warrant was 
executed in ``the ongoing investigation of alleged espionage,'' but 
he would not say where. Neighbors of Taiwan-born American Wen Ho 
Lee said the suspected spy emerged briefly from his home today, but 
didn't say anything. 

</P>
<P>
	Murder Charge in Sex-Torture Case  
</P>
<P>
	TRUTH OR CONSEQUENCES, N.M. (AP) -- A man has been charged in the  
death of a 22-year-old woman whose disappearance is part of a 
10-state investigation into alleged sexual torture and kidnapping. 
While police have said for weeks the case possibly involved murder, 
their searches of a rural home and a lake have produced no bodies, 
including that of the missing woman. The only murder charge in the 
case is the one filed against Dennis Roy Yancy, 27, of Truth or 
Consequences. He was arrested last night and charged in the death 
of Marie B. Parker, 22, who disappeared in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
	Israeli Jets Attack Terrorist Targets  
</P>
<P>
	TYRE, Lebanon (AP) -- Israeli warplanes attacked suspected  
guerrilla positions in southern Lebanon today, Lebanese security 
officials said. Two Israeli fighters fired three missiles at 
targets in a valley between the villages of Jebal al-Botom and 
Zibqine, 10 miles southeast of the port of Tyre, the officials 
said. In Jerusalem, a military spokesman said Israeli air force 
planes attacked ``terrorist targets'' in southwest Lebanon. All 
planes returned safely to base. 

</P>
<P>
	Olazabal Leads Norman at Masters  
</P>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Jose Maria Olazabal shot a 1-over-par 73  
today in the Masters, and Greg Norman is getting yet another chance 
to finally win a coveted green jacket. Olazabal remained in the 
lead at 209, but made a few mistakes today that allowed a host of 
players -- even Tiger Woods and David Duval -- back into the hunt. 
Norman finished off his third round with a birdie to get to within 
one stroke of Olazabal and to earn a date in tomorrow's final 
pairing at Augusta National. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
