<HEADLINE> L.A. Police Honor Captured Soldier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Hours after hopes were dashed that three U.S.  
soldiers in Yugoslavia would be freed, Los Angeles police honored 
the family of captive Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of officers throughout the city on Friday signed 23  
poster-sized placards bearing the captured sergeant's military 
photograph. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez's brother, Steven, is a detective on the force.  
</P>
<P>
	Chief Bernard Parks said the cards were passed around the  
department's 18 divisions to show the family ``what the LAPD family 
is all about.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is my understanding that if Andrew were here he would like  
to be in the LAPD,'' Parks said. ``When Andrew comes back he will 
know so many people thought so highly about him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ramirez's mother, sister and brother, an Army veteran who  
inspired the East Los Angeles native to join the service, accepted 
the cards at police headquarters on a stage decorated with yellow 
ribbons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd just like to thank everybody and express my thanks to them  
and hopefully we'll get my brother home soon so that this whole 
ordeal could go away,'' Steven Ramirez said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly before the presentation, Cyprus president Spyros  
Kyprianou said he had failed to negotiate a release for the POWs in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Ramirez, 24, was captured near the Yugoslav-Macedonian  
border on March 31 with two other soldiers, Spc. Steven M. 
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. 
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich. 
</P>
</TEXT>
