<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 07:51:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Malone Puts the 'M' in NBA MVP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Six-tenths of a second were left on the  
clock. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Utah Jazz down by two points, Karl Malone had just been  
fouled while shooting a 3-pointer. He had to make three free throws 
to steal the game from the Phoenix Suns. 
</P>
<P>
	And Malone -- a 14-year NBA veteran, a former league MVP, the  
soul of workmanlike consistency -- was scared. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I went back (to the bench) to get a drink of water, I  
could not hold on to it,'' he said. ``That's how nervous I was. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was up there (at the line), I was fine. But after I  
went over to get some water, I couldn't drink the water. I was 
shaking that bad. There's nerves in this game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Malone overcame the jitters and made all three free throws  
Friday night, giving the Jazz a 93-92 win. That's what leaders do. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guys are counting on me to hit those shots,'' he said.  
``They don't want to hear excuses. That's what I'm trying to do 
this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By his own lofty standards, Malone fell on hard times during the  
first half of the season. His numbers were down, his shot was off 
and his chances at a second Most Valuable Player Award appeared 
slim. His scoring average, though fourth-best in the league, is 
still at its lowest point since 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	But after leading the Jazz to three impressive wins in the past  
six days, Malone seems to have relocated his game and set his 
sights back on a championship, the only basketball goal he has yet 
to achieve. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people appreciate the things Karl Malone has  
done day in and day out,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. ``He's made 
his body better, he's made his free throws better, he's fought back 
every day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also has rejoined Miami center Alonzo Mourning in what's  
shaping up as a two-man MVP race. 
</P>
<P>
	The two have comparable offensive statistics (Malone is  
averaging 23.5 points per game and Mourning 20.0, while Zo is 
outrebounding the Mailman 11.3 to 9.2), but Mourning is a flashier 
defensive presence and leads the league in blocked shots. However, 
the Jazz have a better record than the Heat. 
</P>
<P>
	In Utah's last three games, Malone has proved his singular  
importance to the Jazz. Sloan, who has coached him since his rookie 
season, said it might have been the finest week in Malone's career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that,'' Sloan said. ``We probably wouldn't have won  
once this week without him. He's won a lot of games for us over the 
years ... and he knows what he has to do. Nobody tells him. He just 
keeps on doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday at Los Angeles, Malone set a Jazz franchise record by  
going 12-for-12 from the field, scoring 30 points in Utah's 106-93 
win against the Lakers. 
</P>
<P>
	Two days later, Malone destroyed the Golden State Warriors with  
a season-high 38 points, including 25 in the second half. He also 
collected 12 rebounds in the 92-85 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-four hours later, he scored 31 points and hit the three  
free throws that doused the Suns. He was a combined 27-for-29 from 
the free-throw line in the final two games, including 13-for-13 in 
the fourth quarters. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been starting to get my groove back for a couple of weeks  
now, and I'm anxious for the playoffs to start,'' Malone said. 
``All I try to do is have one good game and move on. I don't want 
any more pressure on me than I already have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Malone had one other secret he used to keep him focused before  
shooting those pressure free throws Friday night. He took a long, 
slow walk to the other end of the court. 
</P>
<P>
	On the way back, he exchanged a look with John Stockton. After  
nearly 14 years together, that's all the power forward and his 
point guard needed to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want to talk to him,'' Stockton said. ``I just smiled  
and felt confident.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
