<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Carelli Wins at Mesa Marin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BAKERSFIELD, Calif. (AP) -- Rick Carelli came from out of the  
pack to overahaul two race leaders and win the California Truck 
Stop 300 NASCAR truck race Saturday at Mesa Marin Raceway. 
</P>
<P>
	Benefiting from a late tire change on the 254th lap when no  
other team elected to pit under caution, Carelli stormed up from 
eighth-place to catch Ron Hornaday and Kevin Harvick. Their trucks 
had run side-by-side and banged through the closing stages of the 
scheduled 150-mile event. 
</P>
<P>
	When Hornaday and Harvick touched in the half-mile track's  
second turn, on lap 289, and lost momentum, Carelli found the hole 
he needed. The driver from Colorado, who last won in Madison, Ill., 
last August, held on through an additional caution period to beat 
Harvick by 0.759-seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	The runnerup finish was the best of the 23-year-old Harvick's  
career. The Bakersfield native drives a Ford, co-owned by Cleveland 
auto dealer Jim Herrick and retired NBA all-star Brad Daugherty. 
</P>
<P>
	Hornaday, his Chevy's tires losing traction, faded to  
fourth-place, surrendering third to polesitter Stacy Compton's 
Dodge on the final lap. Jimmy Hensley, driving another Dodge, 
finished fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	Carelli, who averaged a near-record 76.331 mph, won $37,780. The  
race, scheduled for 300 laps, went 301 to ensure two laps of racing 
at the conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	The final 12 laps were the only ones Carelli led. The race was  
dominated by Hornaday. A total of six drivers took turns heading 
the 34-truck field, swapping the advantage 14 times. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said earlier today we had a good truck,'' said Carelli, who  
started 26th. ``Last night, we qualified in the dark with what 
seemed like snow and ice and whatever but it came together today. 
</P>
<P>
	``This win means a lot to me. We've had a great truck the last  
few races since we started this season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The finished moved Carelli from 13th in the Craftsman Truck  
Series point standings to sixth place. Hornaday holds a 45-point 
advantage over Compton. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Setzer, who won the race a year ago, finished sixth,  
followed by Jack Sprague, whose effort was marred by two pit road 
miscues. Mike Wallace took eighth, with Butch Miller the final 
lead-lap finisher. Kevin Cywinski was 10th, one lap behind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
