<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Says Hof Farmers Underpayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The battle lines are drawn between the  
Agriculture Department and meat packer Excel Corp. as the agency 
moves forward with charges that the processor underpaid Midwestern 
hog farmers by about $1.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Excel says it will contest within 20 days the charges that it  
violated the Packers and Stockyards Act, which prohibits unfair and 
deceptive practices by packers. 
</P>
<P>
	USDA says it could request that an administrative judge fine the  
company nearly $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint, brought Friday by USDA's Grain Inspection,  
Packers and Stockyards Administration, alleges that Wichita, 
Kan.-based Excel changed the formula it uses to determine how much 
hog farmers are paid without notifying farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	The change allegedly cheated more than 1,250 farmers who did  
business at the company's plants in Beardstown, Ill., Ottumwa, 
Iowa, and Marshall, Mo., by underpaying them for more than 19,900 
hogs in late 1997 and early 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Excel, which controls 9 percent of the U.S. hog slaughter  
market, is a subsidiary of Minneapolis-based food giant Cargill 
Inc. Excel also owns five beef slaughter operations in Nebraska, 
Colorado, Kansas and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	The action ``is legally without merit and was taken without  
first providing adequate notice of an alleged violation,'' said 
company spokesman Mark Klein. ``We're not aware of any other case 
in which (the USDA) has filed a complaint against a company for 
improving the accuracy of a technology or process.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe we would have erred by failing to implement a more  
accurate equation,'' Klein said. The company will pay aggrieved 
producers $1.8 million, but it feels additional penalties would be 
unwarranted, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Klein said the company offered to pay the disputed $1.8 million  
after USDA officials complained that the growers had not been 
notified months after the October 1997 change. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is the formula for which hogs are purchased, known as  
``carcass merit basis.'' A carcass' merit is determined by the 
amount of lean it produced. 
</P>
<P>
	``What they did was reduce the lean value for most hogs, which  
meant that the farmer was getting less money for his hogs,'' said 
Harold Davis, the USDA agency's deputy administrator for packers 
and stockyards. ``The violation here is that they did not tell the 
farmer that they changed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excel counters the new formula was implemented to improve the  
company's pricing system. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company's policy is to use the most accurate measurements  
available,'' Klein said. He said the company contends that some 
producers received slightly lower payments under the change while 
others received higher payments. 
</P>
<P>
	The debate comes as farmers are complaining that big companies  
are pushing them out by keeping prices secret. Vice President Al 
Gore said Thursday that the Clinton administration will push for 
mandatory price reporting among meat processors to ensure that 
farmers have a fair shot in the marketplace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
