<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blue Grass Stakes Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- It's a year of big birthdays for the  
Kentucky Derby and one of its most-traveled steppingstones, the 
Blue Grass Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	A deep, strong field of eight Derby hopefuls is expected for  
today's 75th running of the 1 1/8-mile Blue Grass Stakes. All of them, 
with the possible exception of 30-1 longshot Prado's Landing, are 
being measured as possible entrants for the 125th running of the 
Kentucky Derby at Churchill Downs on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	The field is the largest since 1993 for the $750,000 Blue Grass,  
sponsored by Toyota. 
</P>
<P>
	Nick Zito's Wondertross, bred and co-owned by New York Yankees  
owner George Steinbrenner, was the early favorite coming off an 
impressive close and second-place finish to Vicar in the Florida 
Derby. Vicar was the early second choice, and the field also 
included Cat Thief, third in the Florida Derby, Louisiana Derby 
winner Kimberlite Pipe and Tampa Bay Derby winner Pineaff. 
</P>
<P>
	The other three expected starters in the Blue Grass were Lemon  
Drop Kid, Menifee and Prado's Landing. 
</P>
<P>
	The race is one of three Kentucky Derby prep events today. The  
others are the Wood Memorial at Aqueduct and Arkansas Derby at 
Oaklawn Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Prado's Landing is owned by the United Arab Emirates' Maktoum  
family, who are apparently using his Blue Grass performance as a 
measuring stick for how stablemates Worldly Manner and Aljabr, both 
likely Derby entrants, shape up against the top American 
contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	With such a deep field, today's winner could well end up the  
early favorite for the Derby. That's a dubious distinction, one 
which has not translated into victory at Churchill Downs since 
Spectacular Bid in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless, history shows there's a good chance at least one of  
the colts running in the Blue Grass will make some Triple Crown 
noise. Since 1937, when the Blue Grass was first run at Keeneland, 
17 starters have gone on to win the Derby. The most recent was 
Thunder Gulch, who went from fourth in the Blue Grass to the Derby 
winner's circle in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	In the field of seven 3-year-olds in the $500,000 Arkansas Derby  
were Answer Lively, the 1998 champion 2-year-old colt, second to 
Blue Grass starter Kimberlite Pipe in the Louisiana Derby; Etbauer, 
winner of Oaklawn's Rebel, and Ecton Park, third in the Louisiana 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Badge was to try for was to try for a third straight win and  
fifth in his last six starts when he met 10 rivals in $500,000 Wood 
Memorial. His last victory was in the Gotham. Air Forbes Won, 
Badge's sire, won the Gotham and Wood Memorial in 1982, then 
finished seventh in the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Also in the Wood were The Groom Is Red and Adonis, trained by  
Nick Zito, trainer of Wondertross. The Groom Is Red, who had a good 
2-year-old campaign, failed to win in his first three starts this 
year. In his last start, Adonis finished sixth in the Florida 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the three races was 1! miles. The Kentucky Derby is 1 1/4  
miles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blue Grass and Wood Memorial were to be televised by ABC  
from 5-6 p.m. EDT. The Arkansas Derby was to be on an ESPN telecast 
beginning at 6 p.m 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
