<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hakkinen Wins Brazil GP Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO Brazil (AP) -- The McLarens of Mika Hakkinen and David  
Coulthard filled the front row for the Brazilian Grand Prix 
Saturday, both qualifying more than a half-second faster than the 
rest of the field. 
</P>
<P>
	A surprise was the Stewart-Ford of Brazilian Rubens Barrichello.  
He took the inside of the second row, more than .2 seconds ahead of 
Michael Schumacher and his Ferrari, which was more than a second 
behind the pole-winning Hakkinen. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen, of Finland, averaged 125.412 mph around the 2.687-mile  
Jose Carlos Pace track, just .147 seconds ahead of his Scottish 
teammate. 
</P>
<P>
	No one else in the 21-car field seriously threatened the  
McLarens, but Barrichello excited his countrymen with his fast lap. 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher's best lap put him alongside Barrichello. Italy's  
Giancarlo Fisichella, in a Benetton, was fifth, and the other 
Ferrari, driven by Northern Ireland's Eddie Irvine, was sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	Hakkinen was pleased with his performance.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've made some radical changes to the car, but I haven't been  
able to feel 100 percent comfortable with it in any sector,'' 
Hakkinen said. ``But the pole position must mean we're getting it 
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coulthard praised his car's balance and reliability and said he  
felt very prepared. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't clinch the pole because I overdrove and flat-spotted  
a tire in my last run, so I had to be careful after that,'' 
Coulthard said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today, I had one of the best laps in my entire career,''  
Barrichello said. ``I have been waiting for a good car all my life. 
It goes to prove that all I ever needed was a good car.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he thought he had any chance of winning Sunday's race,  
Barrichello said, ``I don't think I can win if Mika and David are 
on the track. But, it isn't impossible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What I achieved today is a credit to the team and shows that  
Melbourne (where he finished fifth) was no fluke,'' Barrichello 
said. ``What we need for the race is reliability, which all teams 
struggle with at the start of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schumacher was upset with his performance, saying, ``I did not  
expect to be one second off the pole time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We had hoped to be competitive from the start of the season,  
but it seems we have not achieved that,'' Schumacher said. ``It is 
unlikely we can close the gap between now and the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The field was reduced to 21 cars when Brazilian Ricardo Zonta of  
the British American team crashed during practice before 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	Zonta skidded out of control and smashed into a guardrail during  
the second practice session. 
</P>
<P>
	Zonta limped away from the wreckage and was taken by helicopter  
to a hospital where doctors confirmed he ruptured tendons in his 
left foot, ruling him out for Sunday's race. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
