<HEADLINE> Lindros Recovering From Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Eric Lindros was up and about today, a day  
after surgery to remove a hardened blood clot from his chest 
cavity. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Larry Kaiser, a chest surgeon who performed the procedure,  
said he is pleased with Lindros' progress. 
</P>
<P>
	``He look significantly better today than he did before the  
operation,'' Kaiser said. ``His film this morning looks great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser found the Flyers' star center walking up and down the  
hallway with his father, Carl Lindros. Lindros is expected to 
remain in the hospital until early next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The doctor said there was ``very little drainage'' from Lindros'  
chest overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Kaiser had removed a blood clot that was pressing against the  
lower lobe of Lindros' right lung, keeping it from fully expanding. 
Lindros underwent the 90-minute procedure after suffering a setback 
in his recovery from a collapsed lung. 
</P>
<P>
	About six pints of blood to seep into Lindros' chest after a 2-1  
victory over the Nashville Predators on April 1. Kaiser said the 
blood likely seeped from his lung, the result of a blow to his 
chest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
