<HEADLINE> Ex-Chiquita Lawyer Wants Dismissal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- A former lawyer for Chiquita asked a judge to  
dismiss all charges against him in the investigation of voice-mail 
theft at the banana company. 
</P>
<P>
	George Ventura, now an attorney in Salt Lake City, is accused of  
stealing voice mail from Chiquita Brands International Inc. for a 
newspaper investigation of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Ventura filed a motion Friday that claims prosecutors unfairly  
targeted him while ignoring other suspects and methods they used 
violated his constitutional rights. 
</P>
<P>
	He has pleaded innocent to five counts of unlawful interception  
of communications and five counts of unauthorized access to 
computer systems. He could get 12 1/2 years in prison if convicted. 
His trial date is scheduled for April 19. 
</P>
<P>
	Reporters Michael Gallagher and Cameron McWhirter relied on  
voice mail messages in a package of stories last May by The 
Cincinnati Enquirer that accused Cincinnati-based Chiquita of 
improper dealings in Central America. 
</P>
<P>
	In June, the Enquirer fired Gallagher, apologized on its front  
page to Chiquita and paid the company more than $10 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Gallagher pleaded guilty in September to felony charges and is  
awaiting sentencing that could range from 2 1/2 years in prison to 
probation. At a court hearing last week, Gallagher identified 
Ventura as one of his confidential sources. 
</P>
<P>
	McWhirter has not been charged and now works for The Detroit  
News. The News and the Enquirer are both owned by Gannett Co. Inc. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
