<DOCNO> APW19990410.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 15:12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rodman's Wacky Ways Excused in L.A. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- Dennis Rodman has certainly lived up to  
his reputation as weird and distracting 21 games into his Los 
Angeles Lakers career. 
</P>
<P>
	The team wanted his rebounding and defense, which it got. But  
he's done plenty to disrupt, too -- arriving late, not showing up at 
all, taking a leave of absence, refusing to go into games, getting 
ejected and ripping his teammates for their lack of effort. 
</P>
<P>
	It's enough to make Jerry West squirm.  
</P>
<P>
	In one of this city's worst-kept secrets, the team's executive  
vice president -- and classiest Laker of all -- didn't want the 
seven-time NBA rebounding champion, but freewheeling owner Jerry 
Buss insisted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dennis is a talent,'' said Buss, who seems to view Rodman as a  
kindred spirit when it comes to partying. 
</P>
<P>
	During their walk on the wild side, the players are still making  
excuses for the pierced, tattooed and dyed wonder known as the 
Worm. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't been negative that much,'' said Shaquille O'Neal,  
who openly campaigned to get Rodman. ``The stuff that he does or 
did, we all knew it was coming and we all were prepared for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Well, maybe not for all of Rodman's antics. He put the Lakers on  
hold for three weeks before signing, angering part-owner Magic 
Johnson, who spoke for many when he said, ``He's driving me 
crazy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That was just the beginning.  
</P>
<P>
	Rodman disappeared two weeks after joining the Lakers, missing  
four games while he contemplated his basketball future and gambled 
in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Bizarre behavior by most standards; normal for Rodman. He got  
paid during the absence, but said he was fined $100 a day for 
delaying his return. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just gracious of them to let him go to Vegas and do  
some gambling,'' O'Neal said without laughing. 
</P>
<P>
	What have the Lakers gotten in return? An 18-4 record with him  
in the lineup and 11.5 rebounds in 28.8 minutes per game. Without 
Rodman, they are 9-9 and the rebounding falls to O'Neal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I play basketball and I understand the game,'' said Rodman,  
whose personal distractions now include a pending divorce from 
actress wife Carmen Electra. ``I try to let the other players see 
me working hard and watch how I play, and hopefully, they will say, 
`Let's do it, too. He cannot do it all by himself.''' 
</P>
<P>
	That's why his teammates excuse him.  
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of guys in the league and coaches say things about him,  
but they'd all kill to have a guy as dedicated as Dennis,'' forward 
J.R. Reid said. ``He brings a lot to our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly not camaraderie.  
</P>
<P>
	Rodman dresses -- itself a fascinating adventure -- separately  
from his teammates and doesn't talk to them much. When he's not in 
the game, he's rarely on the bench. Instead, he rides an exercise 
bike to stay loose. 
</P>
<P>
	Three times, Rodman has refused coach Kurt Rambis' requests to  
enter games, saying he had been out too long and his muscles were 
tight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I understand ballplayers get stiff, but that's your job to be  
ready the entire basketball game. It doesn't matter if you play two 
seconds or you play 48 minutes,'' Rambis said Friday after Rodman 
refused to return to the court during the Lakers' 96-89 victory 
over the Minnesota Timberwolves. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman spent the entire fourth quarter on the bench despite the  
crowd chanting his name with three minutes left. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman went unpunished for the previous two refusals, and it was  
not known Saturday whether he would be reprimanded for his third. 
</P>
<P>
	Though frustrated, his teammates appear tolerant.  
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have to go to the movies together, eat dinner  
together and do all that,'' O'Neal said. ``But when we're on the 
court, we all have to play together and everybody just has to do 
their part, whether we like each other or not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the fans don't seem to mind. ``Rodman Rules'' and ``Dennis  
the Menace'' were signs held up at the Forum recently. His name is 
welcomed as loudly as that of O'Neal or Kobe Bryant during 
introductions. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman's fourth-quarter ejection after a second technical foul  
against Golden State April 3 was cheered, even though the Lakers 
trailed by four at the time and lost by five. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all cheering his name out there because he works hard  
and his work ethic is incredible,'' Reid said. ``Everything 
concerning basketball you want any player to emulate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Except for the ejections (two) and technical fouls (11). He has  
almost half of the team's 25 technicals. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order for them to do something, I think he's going to have  
to control himself,'' Warriors guard John Starks said. 
</P>
<P>
	Something, of course, is compete for a championship, which  
Rodman has done often in his career. He has five rings, two with 
Detroit and three with Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	But can anyone tame Rodzilla enough in Los Angeles?  
</P>
<P>
	``You don't know what he's going to do, when he's going to do  
it,'' former Lakers point guard Nick Van Exel said. ``Who's going 
to contain him? 
</P>
<P>
	``In Chicago, he had Michael (Jordan) and Scottie (Pippen).  
Here, he's the man, he's won all the championships. Who's he going 
to respect? Who's he going to listen to? 
</P>
<P>
	``Jerry West is not coaching him, Magic is not coaching, so I  
don't know if he respects Shaq as much as he probably should.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The discord triggered by Rodman isn't new to the Lakers. They  
experienced it the past few years with Van Exel, who was traded to 
Denver on draft day last season. 
</P>
<P>
	The fiery guard feuded with former coach Del Harris during the  
playoffs, got suspended for shoving an official and pouted when he 
was unhappy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was never that crazy,'' Van Exel said, comparing himself to  
Rodman. 
</P>
<P>
	For most of their 50 seasons in the NBA, the Lakers have been a  
tame team, winning 11 championships in a dignified way. But that 
was before Rodman arrived in this lockout-shortened season of 
tumult. 
</P>
<P>
	Signing him was one of many moves the Lakers made this season:  
Harris was fired before he could coach Rodman and replaced by 
assistant Rambis; sharpshooter Glen Rice and Reid were added in a 
trade of popular guard Eddie Jones and center Elden Campbell, and 
guard Derek Harper was signed as a free agent. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman's presence has given the mixture volatility.  
</P>
<P>
	``Dennis is Dennis,'' Buss has said. ``You're not about to tell  
Dennis how to be someone else. You take him the way he is.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
