<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Maiden Valhol Wins Arkansas Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Valhol, a maiden making just his third  
start, took the lead on the far turn and then pulled away down the 
stretch to win the $500,000 Arkansas Derby on Saturday at Oaklawn 
Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Trained by Dallas Keen and ridden by Billy Patin, Valhol came  
into the Grade II race for 3-year-olds off a second in a maiden 
race in New Orleans in February and a fourth in the Louisiana Derby 
four weeks ago when he went off at 107-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Certain, who was fourth in the Florida Derby in his last start,  
was a distant second in the field of seven. Torrid Sand, the only 
horse to go off at longer odds than the winner, was third. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who finished out of the money were 2-year-old  
champion Answer Lively, Rebel Stakes winner Etbauer and Ecton Park, 
who was beaten a neck in the Louisiana Derby and had won the Risen 
Star. 
</P>
<P>
	The $300,000 first-place check gave Valhol the graded stakes  
earnings needed to compete in the Kentucky Derby, if the field tops 
20 and his owner James D. Jackson decides to take him to 
Louisville. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're ready for 'em,'' Jackson said. ``That's our next step.''  
</P>
<P>
	The son of Diazo covered 1 1/8 miles in 1:49.1 and paid $62.80,  
$18.80 and $9.80. Certain returned $5.20 and $4, while Torrid Sand 
paid $6 to show. 
</P>
<P>
	Saint's Honor, wearing blinkers for the first time, took the  
early lead with Valhol on his hip. 
</P>
<P>
	They stayed that way down the backstretch with Answer Lively  
third on the outside. Etbauer began to move along the rail heading 
into the turn and Answer Lively began to close on the leaders. But, 
Valhol passed Saint's Honor on the turn and began to widen his lead 
as he hit the stretch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
