<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Menifee Wins Kentucky Derby Prep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Turning for home, Pat Day might have had  
second thoughts about choosing to ride Menifee instead of Cat Thief 
in the Blue Grass Stakes on Saturday at Keeneland. 
</P>
<P>
	With a quarter mile left, Cat Thief, ridden by Mike Smith, was  
in the lead and Menifee was fifth. 
</P>
<P>
	At the wire, however, Menifee was first and Day had his third  
Blue Grass victory and his horse for the Kentucky Derby on May 1 at 
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Day, who had ridden Cat Thief in that colt's previous five  
starts and now has ridden Menifee in his last four, chose Menifee 
despite the colt finishing second in the Tampa Bay Derby on March 
21. 
</P>
<P>
	``When it was all said and done, we thought this horse had a lot  
of room for improvement,'' Day said. ``He showed today he'll take 
it on the chin and keep running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Elliott Walden joked: ``I twisted his (Day) arm on the  
way back from Tampa and it worked.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the top of the stretch, Cat Thief was first, followed by  
Kimberlite Pipe, Vicar and 9-5 favorite Wondertross. Then Menifee, 
four horses wide, charged down the stretch and swept into the lead 
with about a sixteenth of a mile remaining for his second victory 
in three starts this year and fourth in five career outings. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee went 1 1/8 miles in 1:48 3-5. All horses carried 123  
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The winning colt finished 1 1/4 lengths ahead of Cat Thief, who has  
two seconds and two thirds in four stakes starts this year. Vicar, 
the Florida Derby winner, finished another half-length back and 2 1/2 
lengths in front of Louisiana Derby winner Kimberlite Pipe. 
</P>
<P>
	Completing the order of finish were Lemon Drop Kid, Wondertross,  
Pineaff and Prado's Landing. 
</P>
<P>
	Wondertross is trained by Nick Zito, who also trains Adonis,  
winner of the Wood Memorial on Saturday at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, owned by Arthur B. Hancock III and James H. Stone and  
bred by Hancock, earned $465,000 from a $750,000 purse and paid 
$17.40, $8.80 and $5.40. 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief returned $7 and $4.60 and Vicar, ridden by Shane  
Sellers, paid $3.60. 
</P>
<P>
	The farthest Menifee had been in four previous starts was 1 1-16  
miles in the Tampa Bay Derby. As for his ability to go 1 1/8 miles and 
then the Derby distance of 1 1/4 miles, Walden, second in the Derby 
last year with Victory Gallop, said, ``I felt like he had to prove 
it to us. ... He was moving stronger than ever at the finish and he 
galloped out well. I feel good about going a mile and a quarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief and Vicar certainly will join Menifee in the Kentucky  
Derby. So probably will Kimberlite Pipe, Lemon Drop Kid and 
Wondertross, who was beaten 6 1/4 lengths by Menifee. 
</P>
<P>
	Hancock, who won the Derby with Gato Del Sol in 1982, is a  
Kentucky breeder whose father was the famed Bull Hancock. He said 
he was asked Friday night whether he'd rather win the Blue Grass or 
the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, I've been blessed to win the Derby,'' he said. ``I'd  
like to win the Blue Grass.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hancock would take a second Derby victory, too.  
</P>
</TEXT>
