<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Orders More Jets to Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Failure to win release of three U.S. soldiers  
and continued defiance by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic are 
increasing calls in Congress for President Clinton to acknowledge 
that ground forces may be needed to fight the war in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``America, wake up; Europe is at war, and we are in it,'' said  
Rep. Steve Buyer, R-Ind., one of 11 lawmakers just back from a 
visit to NATO headquarters and American troops in Europe. Nine of 
them sent a letter to Clinton on Friday urging him to abandon his 
opposition to a ground offensive. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration continues to oppose inserting American ground  
forces into the conflict, but it said Friday it will soon send more 
warplanes into the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress returns Monday from a two-week spring recess, and  
members are becoming increasingly vocal in addressing the crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton reiterated on Friday that NATO would keep up the  
pressure on Milosevic, even as his administration continued to rule 
out ground forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. Milosevic still thinks he can manipulate the situation by  
cynically using innocent people,'' Clinton said in brief remarks. 
``He hopes that we will accept as permanent the results of his 
ethnic cleansing. We will not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said they were disappointed, but not  
surprised, by the failure of a Cypriot leader to win release of 
three U.S. soldiers held by Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Pentagon, spokesman Kenneth Bacon cited reports that  
young Kosovar Albanian women had been herded into a Serb army 
training camp near Dakovica in southwest Kosovo, where they were 
raped and up to 20 killed. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a very eerie and disturbing echo of documented  
instances of rape and killing of women in Bosnia during the Bosnian 
war,'' Bacon said. ``And it is obviously outrageous that this is 
occurring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bacon also said Defense Secretary William Cohen was expected  
soon to approve a request by NATO's military commander, Army Gen. 
Wesley Clark, for ``dozens'' more warplanes to supplement some 600 
NATO aircraft, half of them Americans. Bombers, fighters, 
radar-jamming planes and refueling tankers are part of the request. 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, all but two of the 11 lawmakers who accompanied  
Cohen to Europe earlier this week urged Clinton to drop his 
opposition to planning for a possible ground war. The group met 
with NATO military planners in Brussels, Belgium, and visited 
American pilots and support forces at air bases in Italy and 
Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the air campaign succeeds in significantly degrading  
Yugoslavia's military capability, ``there is less certainty that 
NATO's broader objectives in Kosovo ... will be achieved,'' they 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe it prudent for the United States to urge NATO to  
plan for additional military missions, including the use of ground 
forces, in the event that proves necessary to carry out such 
missions to achieve NATO's broader objective -- reversing 
Milosevic's genocide actions in Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawmakers said the administration must ``reinforce the point  
to the American public that NATO's efforts could require many more 
weeks or months to succeed.'' And, they said, ``the American public 
also needs to be better prepared for the likelihood of alliance 
casualties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Signing the letter were Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz.; Carl Levin,  
D-Mich.; Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.; Jack Reed, D-R.I.; and Chuck 
Hagel, R-Neb; and Reps. Ike Skelton, D-Mo.; Steve Buyer, R-Ind.; 
Jim Turner, D-Texas; and Ellen Tauscher, D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Not signing were Reps. John Spratt, D-S.C.; and Sam Gejdenson,  
D-Conn. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., and others plan to  
introduce a measure Monday that would invoke the war powers act and 
deny funds for a ground campaign unless specifically approved by 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have learned the hard way, in Vietnam, Lebanon, Somalia and  
Bosnia, that we cannot solve all the world's pressing problems with 
American ground troops,'' said Rep. Roy Blunt, R-Mo., a co-sponsor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
