<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfers Stand Pat at Masters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- It's usually the day for moving up -- or  
moving out. Instead, everyone clustered together during the third 
round of the Masters, leaving the packing for another day. 
</P>
<P>
	No one brought their U-Haul to the course Saturday, despite the  
most favorable scoring conditions of the tournament and a 
leaderboard packed with major winners like Jose Maria Olazabal, 
Greg Norman, Davis Love III, Nick Price, Ernie Els, Lee Janzen and 
Steve Elkington. 
</P>
<P>
	As the day progressed, the patrons waited for someone -- anyone --  
to make a bold move. As it turned out, only a couple of 
lesser-known golfers, Steve Pate and Carlos Franco, managed rounds 
worthy of remembering after a weekend at Augusta National. 
</P>
<P>
	Pate, setting a Masters record with seven straight birdies,  
finished with a 65 and moved within two shots of leader Jose Maria 
Olazabal (7-under 209). Franco, a native of Paraguay, crept into 
contention with a 68, putting him three shots off the lead. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 17 players who left the second round with below-par  
scores, only seven moved further into the red Saturday -- failing to 
take advantage of the light breeze and softer greens. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one really made a move,'' said Scott McCarron, who began  
the day one shot behind second-round leader Olazabal and is still 
only four back despite struggling to a 76. ``I'm at 3 under and I 
still have a chance to win this tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So does much of the field. Twenty-three players go to Sunday  
within six shots of Olazabal, which happened to be the margin from 
first to second in 1996 when Norman suffered his memorable collapse 
and lost to Nick Faldo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought the scoring would be good today,'' said Janzen,  
feeling fortunate to trail Olazabal by only three strokes despite a 
third-round 73. ``But this course has stood the test of time so 
far, and I don't think it's going to roll over now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Olazabal shot a 73 and remained on top. He's the first player  
since Jack Nicklaus in 1972 to hold that position from the second 
to third rounds despite shooting above par on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nice to hang on,'' Olazabal said. ``Actually, I'm pretty  
pleased.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Spaniard was failed by his putter time and time again.  
Despite hitting 12 greens in regulation, Olazabal needed 32 putts 
to get down, after averaging only 25 the first two rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-hole stretch from Nos. 7-12 was particularly galling.  
With a chance to pull away from the struggling field, Olazabal 
missed five birdie putts from 12 feet and closer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't make putts all day long today, completely the  
opposite of yesterday,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone seems to be hanging around -- even David Duval and Tiger  
Woods. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods finally broke par, shooting a 2-under 70, and is five  
shots behind Olazabal. Duval made the turn Saturday at 2 over for 
the tournament, but three straight birdies on the back put him six 
shots off the pace. The pre-tournament favorite would have been 
even closer if not for a three-putt par at 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``In order for me to have a chance to win, I have to get off to  
a quick start tomorrow,'' Woods said. ``Anyone who is 4 or 5 under 
going to the back nine has a good chance of winning.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCarron was a model of consistency the first two days, moving  
into contention with scores of 69 and 68. He was the only golfer to 
break 70 in both rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, the Californian made four bogeys on the front nine,  
then seemed to recover with a birdie at No. 11. But he was forced 
to stand at the 12th tee for more than 10 minutes while Norman, 
playing one group ahead, searched desperately for his ball, lodged 
in a bush behind the green. 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, Norman gave up, walking back to the tee to hit another  
shot. He managed to escape the par-3 hole with a bogey, but 
McCarron wasn't as fortunate. He put his tee shot into some 
shrubbery as well, and wound up with a triple-bogey 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``The 12th hole got me,'' McCarron said. ``But I hung in after  
that. I'm still in this tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Join the club.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
