<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Torre Returns to Yankee Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One day away from Yankee Stadium was more than  
enough for Joe Torre. 
</P>
<P>
	After watching the New York Yankees' home opener on his couch  
with his daughter, Torre made his first appearance Saturday at the 
stadium since undergoing prostate cancer surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was strange not being here yesterday (for the season  
opener),'' the Yankees' manager said from his office in the team's 
clubhouse. ``It was fun to watch, but I felt detached not being a 
part of what went on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre stayed away from the stadium Friday to avoid the  
overwhelming emotion of the day so he wouldn't take away from the 
team and Yogi Berra, who was making his first official appearance 
at the stadium in nearly 14 years. 
</P>
<P>
	So he watched Don Zimmer manage the team from his home with his  
3-year-old daughter, Andrea Rae, who was confused why her father 
was not on television with the rest of the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``She saw Zim talking, she heard them talk about Yogi Berra,  
which got her excited because she thought it was Yogi Bear, and she 
said, 'Where are you daddy?' '' Torre said. ``She thought it must 
be a tape and couldn't understand why I wasn't with the rest of the 
Yankees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I told her if I was there, I couldn't be here with her. So she  
voted for me to stay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Torre said it wouldn't be long before he trades the role of  
babysitter for Yankees manager. He worked out for the first time 
Friday -- spending 20 minutes on the Stairmaster and more time on 
the bike -- and felt less tired at the end of the day. 
</P>
<P>
	His doctor has given him clearance to come back when he feels he  
can handle the pressure that comes with being the manager. 
</P>
<P>
	``From the medical part, I've been given the go-ahead to turn  
loose,'' Torre said. ``When it gets around May 1, it will be close 
to the realistic time for me to get back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the opening day media crush having subsided, Torre made his  
first appearance Saturday. He met with Zimmer and the coaches, 
walked around the clubhouse shaking hands with the players and 
signing some baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just seeing everybody felt good,'' Torre said. ``I  
congratulated them on the emotional win yesterday and how they 
bounced back in Oakland (after an opening-game loss). They seemed a 
lot more relaxed than during spring training.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer, who had dinner with Torre after Friday's opener, was  
happy to see his close friend again. They talk nearly every day, 
but having him at the stadium was special. Giving managing advice 
instead of taking it from Torre would be even better. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I ask him questions about what to do and he gives  
good answers,'' Zimmer said. '' `Do it your way.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer appeared more relaxed, following three wins and his  
cross-country feud with owner George Steinbrenner behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	Torre sat at home and watched as Zimmer and Steinbrenner battled  
verbally about how to use pitcher Hideki Irabu. He even seemed to 
enjoy the view from the outside. 
</P>
<P>
	``I did get a chuckle out of it, even though it probably wasn't  
funny at the time,'' Torre said. ``It was just one of those things. 
The important thing is they respect each other and it went away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon those problems will be Torre's. But for now, he is  
concentrating on getting healthy. He will be back Sunday, and 
possibly in uniform, but only for the World Series ring ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to that,'' he said. ``It will put the  
finishing touches on 1998. The reason you play is for that World 
Series ring.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
