<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 09:21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Raptors Suddenly Lose Their Bite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Regarding those big footprints the  
Toronto Raptors were leaving around the NBA, they're now threatened 
with extinction. 
</P>
<P>
	Just a few days after six straight wins made them the hottest  
team in the East, three straight losses have brought them back to 
reality. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of a sudden, beating Toronto has become important to other  
teams,'' coach Butch Carter said. ``We snuck up on some people, 
booby-trapped them, but right now our intensity is not what it 
takes to win these kind of games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The latest loss was 106-99 Friday night against the New Jersey  
Nets, the team with the worst record in the Eastern Conference. It 
was preceded by losses at home to the Boston Celtics and the Miami 
Heat. 
</P>
<P>
	And after owning the sixth-best record in the East, the Raptors  
now have dropped back into ninth place in the conference, a 
half-game behind the New York Knicks. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a difficult time out there,'' Charles Oakley said. ``When  
we were four games over .500, everything was lovey-dovey. It ain't 
over until the fat lady sings, but we've got to make things happen 
and start playing hard again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Raptors have undergone a major overhaul in the past 14  
months, bringing in three veterans -- Oakley, Kevin Willis and Dee 
Brown -- and asking them to mesh with a kiddie corps long on 
athletic ability but woefully short of winning experiences at the 
professional level. 
</P>
<P>
	Oakley and Willis have helped solve Toronto's rebounding  
problems, while Brown has been a sparkplug off the bench with a 
league-leading 91 3-pointers. 
</P>
<P>
	Combined with the exceptional play of rookie Vince Carter and  
the bench contributions of 19-year-old Tracy McGrady, the Raptors 
have become fiercely competitive while turning into a legitimate 
phenomenon in hockey-mad Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the league has taken notice, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've brought in veteran leadership, and they have learned  
to accept their roles,'' said Cavaliers coach Mike Fratello, whose 
team was run over by the Raptors late last month when they were 
building their six-game winning streak -- the longest in franchise 
history -- with home wins over Chicago, Indiana, Washington and 
Philadelphia and road wins against San Antonio and Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	The bubble began to burst Tuesday when Pat Riley brought a  
fired-up Heat team to Toronto and won by 22. Two nights later, the 
lowly Boston Celtics beat the Raptors by 12 at Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	The common theme in the two latest defeats was an inability to  
stop the opposition's backcourt. It's a matter of hustle and 
quickness, with the Raptors unable to recover after moving over to 
double-team. 
</P>
<P>
	Against Boston, Kenny Anderson scored a season-high 23. Against  
the Nets, Lucious Harris was left wide open and scored four 
consecutive times after Toronto had pulled within three. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams scout you and know your stuff,'' Oakley said.  
</P>
<P>
	``Teams respect us now,'' Willis said. ``They know we're serious  
and they're not going to come in and see us roll over. They're 
ready for us now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of Toronto's remaining 15 games, all are against Eastern  
Conference opponents and only two are against teams that are out of 
the playoff picture. 
</P>
<P>
	And after this weekend, the Raptors won't have another two-day  
break until May 2-3 -- 48 games into the 50-game schedule. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people might be down on us or starting to write us off  
again, but it's just minor adjustments that will give us back that 
winning feeling,'' said Carter, the rookie. ``People are bringing 
their `A-game' now, and we have to be ready for that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In order to make the playoffs, Toronto will need to win at least  
eight of those 15 games -- and maybe as many as 10 or 11. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight will be against Philadelphia, New York, Cleveland and  
Milwaukee -- the teams bunched up along with Toronto fighting for 
the lowest three seeds in the East. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have the experience of being in a situation like  
this,'' Oakley said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just like in the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis fight, we're  
losing the rounds waiting for a decision. But we don't have the 
belt, so we're not going to win the decision like Evander did. 
We've got to keep fighting.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
