<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Joins Medicare Lawsuit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department has joined a lawsuit  
alleging that Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. and Curative Health 
Services Inc. defrauded Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint, unsealed in U.S. District Court in Tampa, Fla.,  
alleges the fraud was related to Curative's management of wound 
care centers at 42 Columbia/HCA hospitals since 1993. Columbia/HCA 
owns 305 hospitals nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	The 42 hospitals charged Medicare for excessive management fees  
that Columbia/HCA paid to Curative, the government alleged. A 
Justice Department statement said those fees were inflated to cover 
the costs of a Curative product for which Medicare does not provide 
reimbursement. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also alleged the hospitals charged Medicare for  
advertising, which Medicare does not cover, and for kickbacks of 
$400 per patient that Columbia paid to Curative for referrals. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospitals violated Medicare's requirement to make only  
reasonable and prudent purchases by including the entire amount of 
the excessive management fees in annual Medicare cost reports, the 
government alleged. 
</P>
<P>
	In early 1993, after Medicare decided not to pay for Procuren,  
an experimental treatment for non-healing wounds, Columbia/HCA 
agreed to amend its contracts with Curative by increasing fixed 
management fees more than 400 percent, by cutting more than half 
the amount charged by Curative for Procuren and by adding a 
management fee of $400 a patient, the Justice Department said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleged the $400 fee violated the Medicare and  
Medicare Anti-Kickback Act. It also said part of the fees paid by 
one hospital were for advertising expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit was originally filed by Joseph Parslow, chief  
financial officer at Southwest Florida Regional Medical Center, a 
Columbia/HCA hospital in Fort Myers, Fla. in 1998. He filed under 
the private whistleblower provisions of the False Claims Act, which 
allows individuals to sue on behalf of the government and receive 
15 percent to 25 percent of any money recovered if the government 
decides the lawsuit is warranted and joins in it. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has joined in several such private whistleblower  
lawsuits around the country to recover triple damages from 
Columbia/HCA for alleged fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, the Justice Department asked for a stay in another  
of those civil lawsuits, saying it was in settlement negotiations 
with the company and moving ahead in the case could hurt the 
government's criminal investigation of the chain's billing 
practices. 
</P>
<P>
	A wide-ranging federal criminal fraud investigation targeting  
Columbia/HCA is looking into whether Columbia overbilled government 
health care programs. Four Columbia executives charged with 
conspiring to defraud the government of $2.8 million have pleaded 
innocent. The company is based in Nashville, Tenn. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
