<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bombing Continues on Holiday Eve  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Despite bad weather limiting NATO  
air operations, bombs fell on Kosovo and air-raid sirens blared in 
several other Yugoslav cities tonight, the eve of Christian 
Orthodox Easter. Dismissing a holiday weekend cease-fire as a sham, 
NATO signaled there was little likelihood of a letup in airstrikes 
tomorrow, the day Serbians celebrate Easter. The head of the 
Serbian Orthodox church, dressed in a traditional white and gold 
gown, conducted midnight mass for several hundred people at the 
Cathedral Church in downtown Belgrade. 

</P>
<P>
	More U.S. Jets to Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dozens of new warplanes are expected to arrive  
for the NATO bombing campaign within days, and Pentagon officials 
are raising the possible need to call up military reserves because 
of the additional U.S. aircraft involved. The Pentagon announced 
that 82 more U.S. planes would join the airstrikes, a move to 
intensify the battle against Serb forces. The introduction of 24 
Apache helicopters, which could take a month to be ready for use, 
would mark an escalation of the war and for the first time allow 
close-to-the-ground, direct strikes against Serb troops and tanks. 

</P>
<P>
	Tornado Victims Brace for Storms  
</P>
<P>
	BLUE ASH, Ohio (AP) -- The hard-hit area of southwest Ohio is  
bracing for a new round of forecasted storms tonight, barely 24 
hours after a tornado killed four and damaged some 900 homes. The 
Cincinnati Bengals' special teams coach Al Roberts had his home 
destroyed in the tornado. ``Understand, there's nothing left,'' 
Roberts said. ``The living room, dining room, kitchen -- gone. 
Upstairs there's (supposed to be) three bedrooms, a hallway, a 
bathroom. Nothing. If you saw the house, you wouldn't know how we 
got out of there.'' 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Searches Home of Suspected Spy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal agents searched the New Mexico home of  
a suspected spy who was fired from his job at a Los Alamos nuclear 
laboratory last month. The raid at the single-story brick and 
wooden home of Wen Ho Lee pierced the tranquillity of the suburban 
neighborhood where the Taiwan-born American scientist lives. 
``There was a lot of commotion going on. People were driving by, 
neighbors were outside and agents were coming and going,'' said 
Phillip Warnock, a neighbor who also works at the Los Alamos 
laboratory. 

</P>
<P>
	US, China Open Agricultural Markets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under an agreement signed with the United  
States today, China will lift its bans on shipments of wheat from 
the Pacific Northwest and citrus from Florida, Texas and 
California. A tentative agreement had been announced Thursday but 
hit a snag when it became clear broader issues concerning China's 
entry into the World Trade Organization would not be resolved 
during a visit to Washington by Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji. 

</P>
<P>
	Fires Keep N.C. Town Residents Away  
</P>
<P>
	WILKESBORO, N.C. (AP) -- A forest fire in the Appalachian  
foothills kept dozens of residents out of their homes tonight as 
firefighters battled the flames. The fire had charred about 400 
acres of forest, mostly on private land, in the area 60 miles west 
of Winston-Salem. More than 50 homes were ordered evacuated 
yesterday, most of them in Pumpkin Run, a subdivision built in the 
past four years in a heavily wooded section. Firefighters continue 
battling the fire into the night, and officials said they hoped to 
have the blaze contained by tomorrow morning. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Beat Devil Rays, 5-3  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Pedro Martinez (2-0) allowed seven  
hits, struck out nine and walked one in seven innings as the Red 
Sox beat the Tampa Bay Devil Rays 5-3 tonight to begin a season 
with five victories for the first time in 53 years. Troy O'Leary 
doubled and homered to drive in three runs in his first two 
at-bats, giving Martinez all the offensive support he needed until 
Tampa Bay began the eighth inning with four straight hits to trim a 
five-run deficit to 5-3. 

</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks' Johnson Ks 15  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Randy Johnson, Arizona's $52.4 million star,  
struck out 15 and pitched a six-hitter to gain his new team's first 
win of the season, leading the Diamondbacks over Tom Glavine and 
the Atlanta Braves 8-3 tonight. Johnson got the 57th complete game 
and 103rd double-digit strikeout game of his career, throwing 83 of 
123 pitches for strikes as the second-year Diamondbacks won for the 
first time in seven games at Turner Field. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
