<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 18:21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Islanders Sign Hobey Baker Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	UNIONDALE, N.Y. (AP) -- Jason Krog, the 1999 Hobey Baker Award  
winner from the University of New Hampshire, signed a two-year 
contract worth slightly over $2 million with the New York Islanders 
on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 5-foot-11, 191-pound center led the nation in scoring last  
season with 34 goals and 51 assists in 41 games. He was the captain 
of the Wildcats, who lost in overtime to Maine in the NCAA 
championship game. 
</P>
<P>
	Islanders general manager Mike Milbury was ecstatic with the  
signing. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of our offseason goals was to acquire talent at the center  
position since Robert Reichel left,'' Milbury said. ``Jason has 
proven to be an extremely productive player on an excellent college 
hockey team. I fully expect him to be with the New York Islanders 
in September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krog said he was happy to have the opportunity to play right  
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to be here,'' Krog said. ``It's a great opportunity,  
and I feel good about my decision.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krog said that there were two factors that he felt led him to go  
undrafted. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not your typical 6-2, 210-pound type of guy,'' he said.  
``I think some teams were scared off by my size. Also, I was a late 
bloomer (talent-wise).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milbury said size was not so much a factor thanks to the  
crackdown on obstruction fouls. 
</P>
<P>
	``Granted, size can be a factor,'' Milbury said. ``But thanks to  
all the obstruction penalties, quickness is just as important. He 
also brings an element of quiet toughness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krog is the fourth Hobey Baker winner to join the Islanders  
organization. The others were defenseman Tom Kurvers and forwards 
Kip Miller and Chris Marinucci. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
