<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 09:15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 15th Hole a Nightmare at Augusta  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- The look on their faces is one of confusion,  
not confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	They cross their arms and stare at a pond that looks like an  
ocean, fronting a green that looks no bigger than a beach towel. If 
the shot is long, making par is not easy. 
</P>
<P>
	``That hole,'' Davis Love III said, ``is scary.''  
</P>
<P>
	Only he's not talking about the 12th, one of the most notorious  
par-3s in golf. 
</P>
<P>
	Of all the changes in the Masters this year, none has had an  
impact like No. 15, the 500-yard par-5 that always has been the 
centerpiece of any Sunday charge at Augusta. 
</P>
<P>
	That's where Gene Sarazen hit ``the shot heard 'round the  
world,'' holing out a 4-wood for double eagle to get into a playoff 
in 1935. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, there was the memorable 15-foot eagle putt by Jack  
Nicklaus on his way to a back-nine 30 to win the 1986 Masters at 
age 46. Mark O'Meara was an afterthought until his birdie at the 
15th last year, the start of his birdie-par-birdie-birdie finish 
for the green jacket. 
</P>
<P>
	When Tiger Woods was romping across Augusta in 1997, he used hit  
wedge for his second shot at No. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	If only it were that simple this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Through two rounds of the Masters, the 15th was averaging 5.097  
strokes. Should that hold up through the weekend, it would be only 
the third time in the history of the tournament that it has played 
over par. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the Masters began keeping such statistics in 1942, the  
15th has been the easiest hole at Augusta. 
</P>
<P>
	Not anymore.  
</P>
<P>
	``You can't hit it on the green with your second shot,'' Love  
said. ``And you can't hit on the green with your third shot. If you 
lay up, you're going to have to hit an absolutely perfect pitch 
shot to get close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Confronted with those circumstances Thursday, Love decided to  
hit a 4-iron. The ball bounced hard over the green and left him 
with this -- 30 feet up the slope to a green that runs hard and fast 
toward the water. He chose the putter, left it 10 feet short and 
gladly took par. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hit it over the green,'' he said, ``and then I laid up.''  
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Sluman wasn't so fortunate. He also hit over the green on  
his second shot, decided to chip and paid for it. The ball trickled 
by the hole, then picked up speed and didn't stop rolling until it 
was floating to the bottom of the pond -- triple bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Mickelson was one stroke out of the lead Thursday when his  
5-iron into the green came up just short. He took double bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the conventional approach.  
</P>
<P>
	David Duval was in the hunt Friday when he played his second  
shot short of the water. The decision left him with indecision. A 
soft sand wedge or a hard lob wedge? He tried to hit a 
three-quarter sand wedge, but the ball spun back off the green and 
into the water. Spooked, he hit his fifth shot over the green, 
chipped on and two-putted for triple bogey. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're not safe with a sand wedge or a pitching wedge, and  
you're not safe with a lob wedge,'' Nick Price said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rough, barely the depth of a golf ball, is only part of the  
problem. About 20 pine trees have been planted down the right side 
of the fairway where there used to be mounds. Even the 
medium-length hitters could use those humps as a slingshot to 
propel the ball down the fairway and leave themselves about a 
5-iron into the green. 
</P>
<P>
	While the rough is hardly U.S. Open material, it's enough to  
keep the ball from rolling down the short grass. 
</P>
<P>
	``I used to hit it up on that hill and kick it back to the  
fairway,'' Scott McCarron said. ``Now I'm trying to hit a 3-iron in 
there, and that's a club or two different.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pin placements have been particularly perilous the first two  
rounds and the green has been difficult to hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``Discretion is very important there,'' Greg Norman said. ``When  
you lay up, the 80-yard shot is almost as hard as the 213-yard 
shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Maria Olazabal tried to play it safe the first day and took  
bogey. He attacked in the second round and made birdie, but only 
after using his superb short game to hit a bump-and-run with a 
9-iron down the slope to about 4 inches from the cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once you hit a tee shot on that hole,'' he said, ``every shot  
is a scary shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It hasn't always been that way. The fairway was always so  
generous that the only problem was going too far left and bringing 
the Georgia pines into play down the left side. If the drive was 
struck well, the only decision was which iron to hit into the 
green, or which part of the fairway to lay to attack the pin with a 
wedge. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could have a big drive or lob it down there, and the hole  
started from 90 yards in,'' Price said. ``Now, the hole starts 500 
yards back on the tee. These people, they must like to see us 
battle here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The battle no doubt will begin on the back nine Sunday, as it  
usually does. The question is whether the 15th again will be a 
launching pad for a fabulous finish or a graveyard where dreams are 
buried. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990410.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 16:32:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Krone Wins Final Hialeah Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HIALEAH, Fla. (AP) -- Julie Krone, making her final ride at  
Hialeah Park, guided Anguilla around fallen favorite Coretta coming 
off the far turn and overtook Winfama at the eighth pole to win the 
$200,000 Black Helen Handicap on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Coretta, an Irish-bred who was sent off at 3-5, was making a  
move from second when she suddenly lost her footing and skidded on 
her chest. I.C. Cindy, running just behind Coretta, bumped the 
favorite and also had to be eased. 
</P>
<P>
	Both horses left the track under their own power and neither  
jockey was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	``She seems to be fine,'' trainer Christophe Clement said of  
Coretta. ``It looked bad, but she apparently came back OK. We'll 
check her out very carefully.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Anguilla moved into second place, then ran down Winfama to win  
by two lengths, covering 1 1/8 miles on the turf in 1:47 2-5. The 
second favorite returned $7.20, $4.60 and $3.80. 
</P>
<P>
	Starry Dreamer closed with a rush for second and returned $7.40  
and $4.80. Winfama held on for third and paid $6.20. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm tickled to win, but it takes something away when it  
happens this way,'' said Tom Skiffington, Anguilla's trainer. ``I 
just hope the mare is OK.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Krone, 35, racing's leading female jockey with more than 3,500  
career wins, announced her retirement Thursday but is honoring her 
riding commitments through next weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had a lot of horse,'' Krone said. ``When I was going down  
the backside, my reins were just splashing around on her neck, she 
was going along so easily. She kept asking me -- `Now? Now?` -- and I 
had to keep telling her `No.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Anguilla, a 4-year-old daughter of Seattle Slew, has won five of  
her last seven starts, finishing second in the other two. 
Saturday's win brought her lifetime earnings to $344,201. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990410.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 07:14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Welfare Rolls Fall Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton today trumpeted a further  
decline in the nation's welfare rolls and announced steps intended 
to keep the numbers shrinking. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationally, just over 7.6 million Americans were receiving  
public assistance at the end of December, down from nearly 8 
million at the end of September and 14.3 million in 1994, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	To continue the downtrend, Clinton also announced final  
regulations to hold states accountable for shifting welfare 
recipients into jobs and give them greater flexibility in using 
federal money to pay for child care, transportation and 
job-retention services. 
</P>
<P>
	``For too long, too many Americans were trapped in a broken  
welfare system that exiled generation after generation from the 
mainstream of American life by cutting them off from the world of 
work,'' Clinton said in his weekly radio address. 
</P>
<P>
	``Reforming our broken welfare system was the right thing to do.  
Now we must finish the job,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the president announced that the number of  
people on welfare had fallen to its lowest level in 30 years. 
Today's figures show a further decrease of 340,000 recipients in 
the three months from October through December 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton placed heavy emphasis on opening doors of employment  
opportunity to welfare recipients, saying that work helps instill 
dignity and purpose in people. For its part, the federal government 
has hired nearly 12,000 welfare recipients, exceeding the 10,000 
goal set two years ago, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulation the president announced today, part of the  
welfare overhaul law Congress enacted in 1996, enforces state work 
requirements and holds states to task for moving welfare recipients 
into jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This regulation says loud and clear people ought to get  
paychecks, not welfare checks,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rule also makes it easier for states to use welfare block  
grants to pay for child care and transportation -- two stumbling 
blocks for those seeking to move from welfare rolls to payrolls, 
the president said. 
</P>
<P>
	He praised the Senate's recent approval of a measure to help  
low-income families pay for child care and made a pitch for his 
proposal to give tax credits and other support to working families. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the falling welfare numbers, Clinton warned against  
forgetting about those who come from poor neighborhoods with 
limited jobs skills and will have the toughest time moving off 
welfare. 
</P>
<P>
	He called on Congress to approve his proposal to extend a  
welfare-to-work program already in place. The administration's 2000 
budget seeks $1 billion to help 200,000 long-term welfare 
recipients in high-poverty areas move to work. 
</P>
<P>
	The president also wants Congress to fully fund a $430 million  
proposal to give housing vouchers that help people on welfare move 
closer to a new job and $150 million in transportation money to 
help people get to jobs, often in suburbs not served by public 
transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990410.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 09:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Springsteen Kicks Off World Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- Reunited with his old band, Bruce  
Springsteen opened his world tour to a sold-out crowd of 20,000 in 
Barcelona's Saint George Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	The Boss did not disappoint in his first tour with the E Street  
Band in more than a decade. They opened Friday with ``My Love Will 
Not Let You Down'' and ``Prove It All Night.'' And that's what they 
did, captivating the crowd for 2 1/2 hours through 19 songs and five 
encores. 
</P>
<P>
	After delighting the Barcelona fans with a greeting spoken in  
Catalan, Springsteen hardly addressed his audience during the 
high-energy performance bursting with old favorites including 
``Badlands,'' ``10th Avenue Freezeout'' and ``The River.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another highlight was a duet, ``Mansion on the Hill,'' sung with  
his wife, Patti Scialfa, who also played guitar and sang back-up 
throughout the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Friday's concert, and a second date Sunday also in this  
northeastern Spanish city, mark the beginning of a 17-city European 
tour for Springsteen and the E Street Band. Dates include Munich, 
Zurich, London, Dublin and Paris before the wrapping up in Madrid. 
The first U.S. performances aren't until mid-July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990410.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-10 09:31:01 </DATE_TIME>
