<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chevrolet Pulls Plug on '99 Monte </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) -- Chevrolet's struggles to get its new Monte  
Carlo on the track during the 1999 Winston Cup season ended 
Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors Corp. announced that it was halting its bid to  
win NASCAR's approval of the new car in time to get it on the track 
this year, and that the 2000 Monte Carlo's Winston Cup debut would 
wait until next year. 
</P>
<P>
	Since most Chevrolet teams had been operating for several weeks  
on the assumption that the new car would not be ready this year, 
Saturday's announcement was a mere formality. 
</P>
<P>
	Chevrolet marketing general manager Kurt Ritter said that even  
if NASCAR were to approve the car immediately, Monte Carlo teams 
don't think they could get a car ready this year without 
jeopardizing their 1999 title chances. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot ask them to take such a risk,'' Ritter said.  
</P>
<P>
	Chevrolet's 12-month quest to get the Monte Carlo approved by  
the sport's sanctioning body has resulted in a car that, according 
to Ritter, would be ``uncompetitive on the race track.'' 
</P>
<P>
	NASCAR officials elected against responding to Ritter's  
assessment. 
</P>
<P>
	GM said the decision to delay the introduction of the race car  
would not affect the street version of the 2000 Monte Carlo, which 
remains on schedule for retail delivery late this summer. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WALTRIP'S LAMENT:* Darrell Waltrip leads all drivers with 12  
victories at Bristol Motor Speedway, but he isn't terribly fond of 
racing on the .533-mile, high-banked oval. 
</P>
<P>
	The reason? When Waltrip was younger, the starting fields at  
Bristol generally were limited to 34 or 36 cars. Now the fields are 
43, a number that Waltrip feels cramps an already tight track. 
</P>
<P>
	``The leader takes the green flag and the 43rd guy is in the  
middle of the back straightaway,'' he said. ``In 20 laps the leader 
is lapping the back of the field. That's not good racing.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TIME TRIALS:* John Andretti led Saturday's second-round  
qualifying for the Food City 500 with a fast lap of 123.905 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Had Andretti gone that fast in Friday's opening round of time  
trials when the top 25 starting spots were set, he would have 
earned the 12th position. Instead, he will start 26th on Sunday's 
43-car grid. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven drivers failed to earn one of the top 36 spots available  
to the fastest qualifiers and had to take provisional starting 
spots. They were Johnny Benson, Ward Burton, Ernie Irvan, Chad 
Little, Jeremy Mayfield, Steve Park and Michael Waltrip. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing to make the field were Stanton Barrett, Rich Bickle,  
Derrike Cope and Carl Long. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *EARNHARDT WRECK:* Seven-time Winston Cup champion Dale  
Earnhardt crashed his Chevrolet in Saturday's final practice 
session. Earnhardt was not injured, but he will have to switch to a 
backup car for Sunday's race, forcing him to start from the rear of 
the field. 
</P>
<P>
	Television replays showed Earnhardt appeared to lose control of  
his car as he went down the frontstretch, setting off a long slide 
that ended when the front end of his car slammed into the concrete 
retaining wall near the first turn. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was loose up off the corner,'' Earnhardt said. ``We kept  
working on it, but it just got out from under me. We'll unload the 
backup car and see if we can get it ready. We can come back and win 
from where we're at.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *C'EST LA VIE:* Michael Waltrip tried to be philosophical about  
damaging the right rear end of his car in a crash during 
qualifying. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're all going to look like this sooner or later at Bristol  
anyway,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
