<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shocked Tornado Victims Clean Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BLUE ASH, Ohio (AP) -- A day after a tornado sliced through  
Cincinnati's northern suburbs, killing four and destroying hundreds 
of homes, residents on Saturday hurried to salvage their belongings 
before another round of storms raked the area. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent Meiser pushed his dented lawn mower off the concrete slab  
that used to be his garage, maneuvered through piles of debris and 
parked it on his pocked front lawn. 
</P>
<P>
	While revving chain saws and rumbling repair trucks blended into  
a background din, Meiser and his wife, Vicki, picked through what 
was left of their home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We lost the garage and the whole roof. They're probably going  
to have to raze it and start over,'' Meiser said. ``We're just 
trying to move things along as fast as possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The state Emergency Management Agency estimated Saturday that  
900 homes were damaged in Hamilton, Clinton and Warren counties in 
southwest Ohio. Red Cross shelters remained open while police 
sealed off streets so repair crews could restore electricity and 
clear debris. 
</P>
<P>
	The predawn storm raced across the county. A tornado briefly  
touched down to the west, jumped back up and came down with full 
fury in Blue Ash and Montgomery, two upscale suburbs. 
</P>
<P>
	Two motorists were killed when their vehicles were flipped off  
the highway. A couple was killed when the tornado leveled their 
house in Montgomery. 
</P>
<P>
	The tornado took off the Meisers' roof, blew out their windows  
and smashed their garage. Neighbors on one side suffered only minor 
damage, and the neighbors on the other side had portions of their 
roof scraped off. 
</P>
<P>
	Across the street, Suzanne Smith's condominium suffered only  
minor damage -- a downed maple tree, a piece of the eaves missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith heard the wind howl, rode out the storm and emerged  
from her condo to see the frightening site across the street. 
</P>
<P>
	``I opened the front door and looked over there and I couldn't  
believe it,'' she said. ``I said, `Lord, don't let me see Vicki and 
her husband trapped.' I went over there and when I got there she 
screamed out, 'We're OK.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Even those who escaped Friday's storm shuddered when they heard  
the forecast. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just very lucky but you know what?'' Ms. Smith said.  
``We're supposed to get more storms at 3 a.m.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
