<HEADLINE> Mets' Piazza Sprains Knee Ligaments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- New York Mets catcher Mike Piazza has two  
sprained ligaments in his right knee, and may be sidelined 2-3 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, who was injured Friday, was sent back to New York by the  
Mets on Saturday for an MRI, which revealed sprained medial 
collateral and posterior cruciate ligaments, Mets spokesman Jay 
Horwitz said Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The MRI did not detect any cartilage damage.  
</P>
<P>
	``The good news is that he doesn't need surgery,'' Horwitz said.  
``The bad news is that it will take 2-3 weeks to settle down. The 
disabled list is a possibility.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza twisted the knee in a rundown during Friday night's 10-3  
victory over the Montreal Expos. He remained in the game for two 
more innings before being taken out for a pinch hitter in the 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza was in the starting lineup for Saturday's game, but  
general manager Steve Phillips, who was in New York, thought he 
catcher should return to have the knee checked by team doctors. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was some swelling and this is very precautionary,'' Mets  
assistant general manager Carmen Fusco said before the diagnosis. 
``He's walking fine on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Piazza, acquired last year from the Florida Marlins after he  
left the Los Angeles Dodgers, is starting a $91 million, seven-year 
contract. He is hitting .429 (9-for-21) with two homers and a 
team-leading eight RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
