<HEADLINE> Fugitive Caught in Dog Cage Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHILTON, Wis. (AP) -- A woman sentenced to a year in jail for  
child abuse that included putting her daughter in a dog cage was in 
custody in Texas on Saturday, nearly two weeks after she failed to 
return to jail after a counseling session. 
</P>
<P>
	Angeline Rogers, 29, and her former cell-mate, Jerri Deadmond,  
were caught in San Antonio Friday evening, said Calumet County 
Sheriff's investigator John Dedering. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities had been searching for the women since March 30,  
when Mrs. Rogers did not return to the county jail after her 
counseling session. Authorities found her car at Deadmond's home. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Rogers and her husband, Michael, were convicted of abusing  
four of their five children, including locking their 7-year-old 
daughter in a dog cage. They were both sentenced to a year in jail, 
with work-release privileges. 
</P>
<P>
	The women were being held in a San Antonio jail Saturday  
awaiting extradition proceedings scheduled to start Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Rogers could face an additional 11 years in custody.  
</P>
