<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Apathy Reigns at Italy's Telecom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TURIN, Italy (AP) -- A meeting of Telecom Italia shareholders'  
fell short of a quorum Saturday, failing to approve a plan to fend 
off Olivetti's hostile takeover bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Failure to have enough shareholders turn out to make the vote  
count raised some eyebrows. One third of the voting shares was 
needed for a quorum, but only 22.5 percent were represented. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing that management didn't know what was going on,  
and it shows that it doesn't have control of the situation,'' said 
Antonio Argentino, a representative of a Telecom employees 
association that backs the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti unveiled its $58 billion proposed hostile bid in  
February, and later sweetened it to $65.2 billion. Olivetti said 
Friday it had submitted a partially complete prospectus to stock 
market regulator Consob to move ahead with the takeover. 
</P>
<P>
	Olivetti also said that its lawyers have contacted Consob to  
force Telecom to make public immediately all the information 
relative to Saturday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Shareholders were supposed to vote Saturday on the conversion of  
some 2.17 billion voting shares into ordinary shares. That would 
have made a takeover far more expensive for Olivetti. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts felt Telecom's failure Saturday to reach a quorum  
might pay off later for the former state monopoly. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecom chief executive Franco Bernabe can now combine  
Saturday's motions with another defensive move: a proposed merger 
with Telecom Italia Mobile, Italy's largest cellular phone operator 
which is 60 percent owned by Telecom. That merger is scheduled for 
shareholder approval in late April. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
