<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steve Pate Not Your Average Golfer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) -- Steve Pate is not your typical golfer.  
</P>
<P>
	It's not that he shot 65 Saturday to land within two strokes of  
the lead heading into the final round of the Masters, or even that 
he got there by making seven birdies in a row, something no other 
golfer has done in the 63 years of this tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	No. What makes Pate different is the way he keeps crashing into  
things away from the golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	He walked into the interview room after one of the most sublime  
stretches ever at Augusta National and spent most of his time 
recounting what he's hit in recent years besides greens in 
regulation. The first collision forced him to take 1996 off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I drove my car into a truck at 75 mph and broke my hand and  
wrist. Probably should have come out a lot worse than I did,'' he 
began. ``Then I broke my left wrist that August. I tripped and fell 
on a dock on vacation with my family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A reporter interrupted. Some priceless Q&AMP;A followed. Here are  
excerpts: 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Where was that?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``Lake Powell.''  
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``And what about the one at Kiawah?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``Some deep muscle bruises. I wasn't driving that time,  
though. I was a passenger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Was that a limo?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``Yes.''  
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``What did I read about the deer accident?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``I didn't get hurt. I got hit by a deer on my bike.''  
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Where was that?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``In my driveway. My dog was chasing it and it broadsided me.  
It was small, around 40 pounds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``A deer got caught in the bicycle's headlights?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``That was it.''  
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Have you had any other weird things happen?''  
</P>
<P>
	A: ``That about covers it.''  
</P>
<P>
	Well, not exactly.  
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, Pate flew as close to heaven as the golfing gods  
allow. For an hour and a half, he couldn't miss. 
</P>
<P>
	He started the day at 2 over par, birdied the third hole and  
walked onto the seventh green after hitting a sand wedge to 7 feet. 
Pate had played Augusta five times before, but not since 1993. What 
struck him as he lined up the 7-footer for birdie was not that he 
might be standing at the threshold of history, but rather that this 
was the ``only straight putt I've ever had here, I think.'' It went 
straight in. 
</P>
<P>
	At the eighth, he pitched a wedge to 20 feet and made it. At the  
ninth, Pate cozied a 9-iron to 1 foot. At No. 10, he drained a 
near-miracle from 45 feet. At No. 11, an only slightly less 
miraculous 30-footer fell. 
</P>
<P>
	At the graveyard-of-champions 12th, Pate ended any suspense  
about tying the record of six consecutive birdies held by Johnny 
Miller, Mark Calcavecchia and David Toms by sticking an 8-iron less 
than a foot from the hole. 
</P>
<P>
	About the time he pulled the ball from the hole, Pate looked  
back to see thousands staring at him. His playing partner, Lee 
Westwood, and his caddy, Allan Mellan, were staring, too, 
determined to treat Pate like a pitcher throwing a perfect game. 
Both kept telling themselves over and over, ``Stay out of the 
way,'' but refused to say a word, lest they break the spell. 
</P>
<P>
	The galleries, though, were roaring.  
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``How many people started watching you today as opposed to  
how many people finished watching you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A: ``That's a good question. I know there were a lot of people  
in the middle of the round. They started appearing out of nowhere, 
out of the trees, like Big Foot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Steve, after that birdie on 12, you kind of walked back  
into the woods a little bit. What were you doing?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A: ``Tucking in my shirt.''  
</P>
<P>
	At the par-5 13th, Pate hit a 3-wood off the tee, 5-iron down  
the fairway and tucked a lob wedge to within 7 feet of the flag. He 
made that for the record. 
</P>
<P>
	For all the mirth and composure Pate showed on this day, it's  
worth mentioning that his chief sponsor is Tabasco brand hot sauce 
and his professional nickname is ``Volcano.'' Pate got the former 
for the same reason a PGA Tour official gave him the nickname at 
the start of the decade-- at outsized temper, occasionally displayed 
on the heels of a bad shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Steve, are you still a volcano or did that disappear after  
the injuries and the year off?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't say it's disappeared, but it's gone way in the  
background since the year off. After getting in a serious car 
accident, somehow hitting a bad shot doesn't seem quite as big a 
deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If Pate plays the final round the way he did the third one,  
though, it will be the biggest deal in a career not exactly 
bursting with them. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: ``Will you be walking to the course tomorrow with all your  
accidents and run of bad luck?'' 
</P>
<P>
	A: ``Oh, no. I believe in taking chances.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
