<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brothers Arrested in Vegas Robbery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- With helicopters hovering,  
camouflage-clad police swarmed on a remote mountain hideaway and 
arrested two brothers in connection with a $1.6 million armed 
robbery in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Alan Gonce, 59, and Fain T. Gonce, 63, were taken into  
custody Thursday for the Dec. 28, 1997, armed robbery of the United 
Coin Machine Co., said state police officer Mike Applegate. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen members of the state police tactical team,  
supported by Las Vegas detectives and sheriff's deputies, raided 
the brothers' isolated home near the Gila National Forest of 
southwestern New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials of United Coin, which services Las Vegas slot  
machines, did not answer calls seeking comment today. 
</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas police said the 1997 robbery was carried out by two  
armed men wearing ski masks and jumpsuits while a driver waited 
outside. 
</P>
<P>
	Applegate said a third suspect in the heist, Eric Zessman, was  
arrested Thursday in Pahrump, Nev., by Las Vegas authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Police confiscated about $32,000 in cash, gold and silver coins  
from the brothers' place, along with property warranty deeds and 
receipts for $50,000 in mutual funds and other items, Applegate 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officers also took about 30 weapons, including two that Las  
Vegas police suggest could have been used in the United Coin heist 
-- a .20-gauge shotgun and a 9mm semiautomatic pistol, Applegate 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Why they were stockpiling all that ammunition, I don't know,''  
said sheriff's deputy Ron Hays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
